psychedelic  ✊🏻keyswords ✊🏻 you shouldn't feel anything ? ok   i see this said a lot around the sub and in other places about microdosing.- *you shouldn't feel anything*.  do you think that statement is not very accurate and can be somewhat confusing to newcomers?  if you are an experienced microdoser and have read other people's anecdotal reports or guides, do you think it would be more accurate to tell someone what the negative things they should **not be feeling when taking a proper microdose? for example-  you should **not feel: - high - spacey - impaired - confused - unable to focus or concentrate - jittery - hallucinate, have visuals or distortions in your vision  - tiredness   now if you do feel any of those things then that probably means you took too much, you may have a low tolerance, or it's pretty potent, and so you should probably adjust your dosage.  (unless of course you like feeling some of those or seeing visuals during your normal day🙃🤩.) personally i prefer to double up or take a slightly higher dose sometimes if i have nothing to do that day, set my intentions, be in a relaxing environment, maybe listen to some guided meditation and really just let go.   remember though that's not always for the faint of heart though, and for those that might be new to psychedelics and have a predisposition to anxiety, bipolar, schizophrenia or any family history of it should be really careful and probably stay away from psychedelics. please do not self-medicate with psychedelics especially if taking other medications, and doctor 🎯🔌.     psychedelic agent  👻    telegram 🔞 location fl it's important to also stay in a good set and setting, and it might not be a bad idea to have someone with you, just in case you take too much. if you do take too much, (like i did one time and started having a panic attack and thought loop started), then maybe [this might help!]comments/fe1luu/if_you_start_to_feel_anxious_some_paranoia_panic/).  **reminder:** the recommended starter dose for "micro-doses" are 0.05g-0.1g of bone dry, ground up and mixed p. cubensis mushrooms; or around 0.3 grams of dried truffles. if you use fresh truffles, you probably need around 0.5g. if trying lsd only 5ug-10ug.  edit: if you are highly sensitive to certain drugs then you may want to adjust your dosage. also don't forget potency can vary with tabs of lsd, mushrooms types and their stems and caps. that's why it's important to grind and mix them really good and start low.   **now the positive things that most people have reported that they perceive *feelings of or a sensation of* can be any of the following. -**  - joy, happy, content, uplifted feeling - more aware of one's surroundings - more open in social situations, connectedness  - flow - stillness, calm, in the present moment - shift in thoughts or awareness - heightened alertness, awareness, emotions or sensitivity - compassion - gratefulness  - boost in creativity  - a boost in energy and productivity (or not)  unfortunately in some cases it could cause individuals to be tired or sleepy and in others that might have a predisposition to anxiety then it could raise anxiety levels or make you hyper like too much caffeine. this can be especially true when microdosing lsd or when you haven't prepared yourself for it. it may also amplify your suppressed emotions sometimes, so be sure you set your intentions and have a good emotional support plan in place. you can read more on that [in my older post here]👆⛑some_selfhelp_and_resources_for_people_looking_to).  of course those positive feelings or sensations in the 2nd list may vary per individual and usually happens gradually over time. in some cases a month or more. (took me about 6 weeks to really see the true benefits.) others have reported less than 2 weeks, or even just after the 1st dose a overall sense of feeling positive.   the point is, our brains, bodies and nervous systems are unique, and this is still all somewhat an experiment, so it can have different effects on you and it's not always meant to be used by everyone. remember you are experimenting with some pretty potent psychedelic stuff, so please use caution and practice harm reduction. don't try it your first time at work, school or on a day of important obligations or responsibilities. hopefully you'll find your sweet spot dose soon enough where you don't feel those negatives, just the positives. if you do still feel those negatives after trying for a while, then unfortunately microdosing psychedelics might not be the right choice for you, or you need to combine it with other therapeutic tools, or just go all out and do a macro therapeutic guided trip with supervision and under a good set and setting   what do you think? maybe other experienced microdosers can share and expand on this?  also on the subject of sub-perceptual, which has been brought up before in other posts, instead of using the term sub-perceptual maybe it would be better to say sub-hallucinating or sub-threshold or something similar? got any better verbiage?

you shouldn't feel anything ? ok   i see this said a lot around the sub and in other places about microdosing.- *you shouldn't feel anything*.  do you think that statement is not very accurate and can be somewhat confusing to newcomers?  if you are an experienced microdoser and have read other people's anecdotal reports or guides, do you think it would be more accurate to tell someone what the negative things they should **not be feeling when taking a proper microdose? for example-  you should **not feel: - high - spacey - impaired - confused - unable to focus or concentrate - jittery - hallucinate, have visuals or distortions in your vision  - tiredness  👻add snapchat  now if you do feel any of those things then that probably means you took too much, you may have a low tolerance, or it's pretty potent, and so you should probably adjust your dosage.  (unless of course you like feeling some of those or seeing visuals during your normal day🙃🤩.) personally i prefer to double up or take a slightly higher dose sometimes if i have nothing to do that day, set my intentions, be in a relaxing environment, maybe listen to some guided meditation and really just let go.   remember though that's not always for the faint of heart though, and for those that might be new to psychedelics and have a predisposition to anxiety, bipolar, schizophrenia or any family history of it should be really careful and probably stay away from psychedelics. please do not self-medicate with psychedelics especially if taking other medications, and consult a doctor first.  it's important to also stay in a good set and setting, and it might not be a bad idea to have someone with you, just in case you take too much. if you do take too much, (like i did one time and started having a panic attack and thought loop started), then maybe [  **reminder:** the recommended starter dose for "micro-doses" are 0.05g-0.1g of bone dry, ground up and mixed p. cubensis mushrooms; or around 0.3 grams of dried truffles. if you use fresh truffles, you probably need around 0.5g. if trying lsd only 5ug-10ug.  edit: if you are highly sensitive to certain drugs then you may want to adjust your dosage. also don't forget potency can vary with tabs of lsd, mushrooms types and their stems and caps. that's why it's important to grind and mix them really good and start low.   **now the positive things that most people have reported that they perceive *feelings of or a sensation of* can be any of the following. -**  - joy, happy, content, uplifted feeling - more aware of one's surroundings - more open in social situations, connectedness  - flow - stillness, calm, in the present moment - shift in thoughts or awareness - heightened alertness, awareness, emotions or sensitivity - compassion - gratefulness  - boost in creativity  - a boost in energy and productivity (or not)  unfortunately in some cases it could cause individuals to be tired or sleepy and in others that might have a predisposition to anxiety then it could raise anxiety levels or make you hyper like too much caffeine. this can be especially true when microdosing lsd or when you haven't prepared yourself for it. it may also amplify your suppressed emotions sometimes, so be sure you set your intentions and have a good emotional support plan in place. you can read more on that [in my older post here]👆⛑some_selfhelp_and_resources_for_people_looking_to).  if looking forward to get psychedelic add snapchat   of course those positive feelings or sensations in the 2nd list may vary per individual and usually happens gradually over time. in some cases a month or more. (took me about 6 weeks to really see the true benefits.) others have reported less than 2 weeks, or even just after the 1st dose a overall sense of feeling positive.   the point is, our brains, bodies and nervous systems are unique, and this is still all somewhat an experiment, so it can have different effects on you and it's not always meant to be used by everyone. remember you are experimenting with some pretty potent psychedelic stuff, so please use caution and practice harm reduction. don't try it your first time at work, school or on a day of important obligations or responsibilities. hopefully you'll find your sweet spot dose soon enough where you don't feel those negatives, just the positives. if you do still feel those negatives after trying for a while, then unfortunately microdosing psychedelics might not be the right choice for you, or you need to combine it with other therapeutic tools, or just go all out and do a macro therapeutic guided trip with supervision and under a good set and setting.   what do you think? maybe other experienced microdosers can share and expand on this?  also on the subject of sub-perceptual, which has been brought up before in other posts, instead of using the term sub-perceptual maybe it would be better to say sub-hallucinating or sub-threshold or something similar? got any better verbiage? snapchat 👻

you're tripping on serotonin from the day you're born but after a couple years it becomes familiar (reality). when you replace the serotonin with a psychedelic analog, the subjective experience changes to the unfamiliar, and you have to get used to existing all over again.   things that you thought mattered, don't matter; things that you thought were useful, aren't. starting over from scratch is just too scary for some to handle, but for others it's a whole new lease on life. in other words, it's useful to see things a different way, if you can make use of it. if you aren't prepared to see things a new way, the psychedelic experience is at best utterly confusing and at worst, existential torture. that's why we have bad trips.  the release of dmt at death is the last trip you get- if you are ready for it (death), you see your whole life in a new way, and if you aren't... your last moment is existential torture. heaven and hell.   hi andy thanks for the challenge.   i believe serotonin is central to the phenomenon of experience because of the roles it is evidenced to play in both learning/memory and emotion, as well as in sleep. these three happen to be very important attributes of the human experience, and of that of complex life on earth, in general, which is why i attach so much significance to this neurotransmitter. of course other chemicals, especially dopamine (but also including gaba, acetylcholine, and so on), are essential to the function of the brain, but something about substituted tryptamines is especially suggestive in the profound and meaningful experiences they generate. this as opposed to the delirium induced by gabaergic compounds like agarin, another dr. peterson favorite, for example.  drugs that impact serotonin levels (such as ssris & maois) do affect our subjective experience; why else would we use them? they don't cause "hallucinations" or "altered states of mind" because they do not change the structure of neurotransmitters available to the brain, only the quantity, bioavailability, and/or efficiency of familiar neurotransmitters, but nevertheless they do impact state-of-mind-as-such in that they regulate mood, etc. however, these same drugs also enhance the effects and potency of various psychedelic tryptamines, which further suggests to me that the body utilizes these analogous tryptamines via a similar mechanism as, and to serve a similar function to, serotonin (5-ht).  their sometimes subtle (dmt, psilocin, bufotenin) and sometimes not-so-subtle (lsd) differences in chemical structure result in a variably augmented performance in accomplishing the various computational tasks of serotonin, which manifests in the subjective experience as an "altered state of mind".  incidentally, lsd is also analogous to the neurotransmitter dopamine, in a manner similar to that of the psychedelic phenethylamines (mescaline, mdma, 2c-x)... although it is hitherto unique in that it is active to both dopaminergic and serotonergic receptors, qualitatively exhibiting augmented traits of both neurotransmitters when introduced to the brain.  dopamine is the chemical responsible for the experience of reward/motivation, motor control and addictive behavior--but despite lsd and the phenethylamines' similarity to dopamine, they are practically nonaddictive.  i believe this proves my point. similar to the case with ssris and serotonin, drugs like nicotine, cocaine, heroin and alcohol are addictive because they achieve something that activates the release of endogenous dopamine; lsd and the phenethylamines are nonaddictive because they replace dopamine and do not trigger that release, but meanwhile they augment the utility and function of dopamine receptors regarding the computational processes of the brain, which manifests itself as an altered state of mind.  i suppose what i am getting at is this obvious truth: that there is no separation between sensation, subjective experience, and neurochemistry. changing neurochemistry inevitably changes computation, thus perception, thus subjective experience. by studying these qualitative changes relative to what we know about the altered chemistry, we can arrive at conclusions about the function of our natural chemistry as well as hypotheses on the mechanisms behind cognition itself.  i myself have arrived at these conclusions based on extensive... uh.... research. sorry if this was totally incomprehensible, but i can only explain it the way i understand it.  then again, that too is part of the human experience. i have a feeling that if we all used the same words, we would find we agree on more things than we disagree on.  edit: that's what i get for not proofreading   not proven, and sadly not provable today. unless you are willing to conduct an experiment putting probes into the pineal glands of dying human subjects. dmt has been detected in the pineal glands of other mammals that science is less scrupulous about, however, and because of structural and chemical similarities it's reasonable that human pineal glands are also capable of producing dmt. it's a popular hypothesis to explain mystical experiences, including near death experiences.  if you're interested in the topic i'd recommend reading dmt: the spirit molecule, by dr. rick strassman. to my knowledge strassman is the only researcher to have conducted gov't-approved experiments with dmt on human subjects, and he makes some interesting observations there

anadenanthera columbrina is the tree that contains naturally 5-meo-dmt, that can be used as an alternative to the toad. it probably feels slightly different, but the medicinal effects are probably the same.   the trees are pretty widespread, unlike the toads. they are also known as "vilca" (sacred trees) and used to be used to produce a fermented hallucinogenic beer by pre-mayan cultures... which probably led to ayahuasca usage.  it's related to a lot of native and non native plants, such as honey locust trees, or albizia julbrissin, which contains a high percentage of bufotenine... which i find preferable to some dmt analouges, as it is very non - hallucinogenic, and extremely calming and healing.   i'm kind of high strung so any edginess to any chemicals really brings that quality out in me.  the more people use these substances, the more neccessary it is to develop proper practices and techniques surrounding their usage and production methods, while making sure to preserve nature as it is.

i love your stuff but no mental health problems meet the criteria for being a disease. a disease has to have a single cause specific to that disease, a limited and specific set of signs, each of which can be objectively measured and that explain the limited and specific symptoms peculiar to that disease. as lucy johnstone points out in 'users and abusers of psychiatry' most mental health disorders barely meet the criteria for syndromes. for depression to be a disease all depression in every individual with depression would have to have a single cause that was completely different to clinical anxiety, completely different to the single cause of schizophrenia and all the other conditions manufactured for the dsm v and the icd.   see also, 'madness explained' by professor richard bentall, also 'the emperor's new drugs', by professor irving kirsch, also 'let them eat prozac' by professor david healy. from toyooka et al, 2002 as i remember, it seems that brain derived neurotrophic factor, (bdnf) may be more important in improving depressive symptoms than either serotonin or dopamine.  interestingly in depression, fibromyalgia syndrome, (fms) and chronic pain there are similar issues in the circulation in the pre-frontal associative cortex, (pfac). also there are other physiological similarities across these conditions with depression also being an inflammatory condition with a particular effect on calcium metabolism  and is now recognised as a cause of osteoporosis. there is increasing research regarding nutrition/diet and mental health, see 'unprocessed' by kimberley wilson, where there are clear synergies with exercise, noting that exercise promotes effective and targeted increases in bdnf.  i worked as a physiotherapist in mental health for the best part of thirty years and had to argue my corner as the absurd perspective, even as late as the first decade of the 21st century is that, somehow, the mind and body were not really connected. nevertheless dangerous chemical interventions and the even worse ect were constant forms of 'treatment'. psychiatrists generally could not get their heads around the fact that food can be analysed in terms of its chemical profile or were aware of pharmaco-nutrition or the work of pfeiffer in relation to orthomolecular psychiatry.  i too believe, because of the emergent evidence, that psilocybin, mdma and lion's mane have therapeutic benefits but, as the psychologist oliver james points out in 'the selfish capitalist' we have produced a socio-economic system and culture that is a  perfect manufacturer of mental ill-health and with vested interests in promoting reliance on drugs (n.b. the bps and american psychological association consensus statement on the dsm v (as a self-serving work of fiction). also look at the success of the soteria project described in the book 'models of madness' edited by mosher, read and bentall, although that was with people denoted as suffering from schizophrenia. taking any form of 'medication', no matter how useful, will not deal with the social and economic influences that undermine mental health and overall well-being.  as i said, i really have appreciated your output over covid, as a sane voice challenging a medicalising and profit focused narrative in the face of a reflexively censorial and authoritarian government. however a similar narrative has also dominated our thinking regarding mental health problems, the real epidemic or our times, and for the same reasons, power and profit.  all the very best to you.

dmt is almost invariably going to be in freebase form, which is best for vaporizing or smoking, which the route of administration that almost everyone uses for the compound. snorting the freebase form is definitely going to burn like crazy. similarly, the freebase form of 5meo is optimal for vaporizing or smoking and that would also burn badly if snorted. however, either molecule can also come in a salt form such as hydrochloride, fumarate, succinate, etc. salt forms are best suited for intranasal, rectal, intramuscular or intravenous routes of administration because they are far more water soluble and far less harsh taken on membrane and tissue. also worth noting, freebase can be converted to salt and vice versa.   these compounds are vastly different experientially. i recommend fasting for far longer than three hours. i've purged (vomited) having eaten only a small meal of chia pudding six hours prior. that might have had more to do with needing to let go of something psychologically and emotionally than the food itself, but i feel it's beneficial to fast for quite a bit longer. i usually aim for 12 hours or more, consuming no food whatsoever and only small amounts of water on the day of my journey. i believe the low-and-slow method--starting small and working up incrementally to the breakthrough---is a wise approach, especially for someone's first 5meo experience. i know several facilitators who serve this way. they first offer what's known as a "handshake" dose, a small amount that gives the participant a chance to feel the substance without potentially being overwhelmed and that allows the facilitator to gauge the response both physiologically and psychologically. this is crucial in particular to make sure there are no signs of potentially dangerous reactions. you can always take more but you can't take it away once it's in you. assuming there are no issues, these facilitators would then proceed to a "hug" dose, a medium dose that goes deeper but is still short of the full-blown experience for most people. however, it's important to note that individual sensitivity to 5meo can vary drastically. for some people the medium dose might be completely overwhelming and they might not wish to proceed, and for others it might actually result in a full-release experience with no need to go any higher. for those who do need more to have the full-release experience, facilitators would offer a third "full embrace" dose, which can be dialed in based on observations from during the small and medium-dose journeys.

please delete your own post so anyone who deals with mental illness doesn't see this and is triggered. because this comment is a judgmental one and the reason many  people have suffered with mental illness without seeking help. it's that idea of "just get over it." would you tell a diabetic just get over it? a diabetic takes medication, eats a proper diet, exercises to manage the disease, but still has the disease and may experience setbacks from time to time. mental illness is an illness for which you may or may not need medication (depending on your condition), watch your diet, exercise, go to therapy, do whatever to learn how to manage your illness. sometimes you have setbacks. and if you are in a marriage with someone who has an illness, you don't leave if you are committed, i mean if you truly meant your vows of "for better or worse, for richer or poorer, in sickness and health, til death do us part." i get that having this level of commitment is not for you. but please don't assume that a person with mental illness can "just get over it."   why do some people with great homes, great families, great careers still have chronic arthritis, still have lupus, or still have diabetes, like i mentioned? because these illnesses have nothing to do with those exterior things. these illnesses are inside a person's body for whatever reason. having a great home, job, and family doesn't prevent you from having those illnesses. just like having those things isn't going to prevent you from having mental illness. you go to doctors, specialists to learn how to manage arthritis, to learn how to manage lupus, to learn how to manage diabetes, and yes even how to manage mental illness. it's hard being in a relationship with anyone who has any illness. and if you make the choice to be with that person, yes you are making the choice to deal with their illness too.

when it was time for my opening, i meditated for a month straight. when i walked places, when i ate, when i sat, i meditated. i got to that same place of realization that you had on this drug. it seems to be where we're going. the veil is fading away. we're becoming awake. yea! i agree. it's an inner experience that seems to be what really is.   hello akshay. i had just moved to ireland from the u.s. after a really difficult life. i had never meditated before. i read a book that described our world like film from a movie. if you look at the way it works, each separate picture makes us see movement. so i, not having a life at that time, just made every thought to picture the in-between. i didn't know about breath, or technique of meditation. i was able to see life from another higher perspective. i saw myself walking in front of me. i was light. it only lasted for a short time, but changed everything.   not too long ago, movies were made on film and put onto a reel. there were hundreds/thousands of frames - each one had a picture almost exactly like the one before, with a slight difference. when you  spun the reel on a projector, it looks as if it's constant movement. what i would do is put myself in a constant flow of trying to be in the part between each frame/picture. while i walked, got on the bus, ate, etc., i would concentrate on just that. one of the days, as i was walking to the market, i felt things i had learned to the fullest. i had taken psychology, and it was like one of the greats let me in their mind. i felt that if i put myself in the mind of an alheimers person, or a baby, someone without language, i could go so much further with this. my mind had totally expanded. when walking back from the store, i was totally in the zone. i was expanded. i could see me walking about 25 feet in front of me. i was light. when i tried to think of how i'd explain this, it faded. i had another very cool thing happen a few years later.  different, but fascinating.  for another time. take care akshay. p.s. the reason psychedelics work so well is they instantly put you in a place where you're not in the past and not in the future. you're completely in the present moment. the magical place. we can learn to do this. either way is amazing.

it's more about starting set and setting and if your mindset is good once you've started properly tripping you'll know if you'd be okay outside in urban environments etc or not. preferably home or nature is better though imo but it's all subjective what does it feel like headspace wise at that dose with visuals that strong? most of these are probably lsd/shrooms but some of the more intense ones like at the end are dmt most likely. the effects are all subjective though so it's hard to say. shrooms feel ancient and archaic and natural and the visuals seem to fall in line with that, acid feels like the universe directly communicating with you and the visuals are more intense imo why lol, bright colours are beautiful   i freaked out on my first trip, it was a fairly low dose of acid so not much visuals, but just being in such a different headspace was a headfuck for me and i made the initial mistake of resisting. i eventually realised i'm in for the ride now and i have to make the most of it, so i went outside to gather my thoughts and all my worries and anxiety melted away as i went out into nature. i returned home and into my back garden where i watched the night sky, the clouds looked so beautiful. i grabbed a joint i rolled up earlier and took a hit or two and put on some background music.  then my visuals really geared up a ton. i sat in absolute awe as i saw the clouds move in and out towards the moon like waves at a shore. the moon itself looked magnificent and awe-inspiring, like a god. then the clouds cleared and i saw hundreds or maybe even thousands of stars appear in the sky, all dancing together in unison.  i took the lsd because i heard of the effects of mental health and had already tried several antidepressants, therapy and a variety of other attempts to sort myself out. i was suicidal at this point and was seriously close to actually doing it. this was my last attempt at sorting things out - boy did it work.   i then lay on the ground to get a better view of the stars, and i cried and cried absolute tears of humility and awe and splendour and joy. i felt so tiny, and so did my worries and pain, it all shrank into something so insignificant. here i was, about to throw my life away after i had not existed to see the universe for billions of years and possibly never will see it again, and in this short timeframe i have of human life i have the world at my fingertips. this absolute paradise planet, through all the flaws of humanity and the darkness we go through, there is nothing more worth experiencing than life here.   it felt like the universe was talking to me, telling me everything will be okay and i have nothing to worry about. i cried on the phone to my dad that night who didn't even know i was contemplating suicide, and i told him everything and that i no longer wanted to end things.  i still struggle with depression ofc as i'm only human, but those feelings are so much more insignificant and manageable now. i have so much more appreciation for life and the beauty of this universe and since then i have had no suicidal thoughts.  i've had other trips since then on both lsd and psilocybin, and they each teach a valuable lesson. the hard part is learning to take the message from your trips and integrate them into daily life.  this stuff is insanely powerful and profound and if you do some research to make sure you're in a good place and everything is safe, etc. you will have a good time.   good set and setting, set an intention for what you want from the trip and then once you've taken it - let go. sometimes your intention happens, other times trips give you what you need and not what you want but learn to let go and you will have some of the most memorable and possibly healing experiences of your life

i had a dream where i realised i was dreamng and woke up in the dream then i could imagine something and it would happen i just wanted to randomly share something with you guys most people don't know. i've told like 3 people this. it's going to be kind of long, but if you guys are into metaphysical stuff, it'll be interesting, i promise you. this is 100% true  so, august 2017, i attended 515 music festival (i was completely sober the whole time, so don't account this experience to drugs). the last night, after the festival, i was with my friend on the 2 hour ride back home. he was driving and i was trying to get some rest.  it's important to know that i have periodical heart complications. anyway, he stopped somewhere, i don't remember where it was, i feel like it was on a gravel road (because he couldn't find anywhere open) to go pee. i briefly remember the vehicle stopping and him saying "i'll be right back man", and i just kind of nodded and closed my eyes again. i hear his door close, and i am alone in the vehicle.  shortly after, my heart makes a few off rhythm, incredibly heavy beats. it felt like it was going to jump out of my chest. after that, it physically felt like someone had my heart in their hands and they were squeezing it as hard as they could. at this moment, i was having a seizure, in which i mean i started twitching uncontrollably. it stopped and i became incredibly calm, as i felt (myself?) shoot up out of the vehicle at impossibly fast speeds, sort of like i was going through a wormhole.  when my journey came to an end, i found myself laying on the ground somewhere, except it wasn't ground in a physical sense.. everything was incredibly etheral. the "walls, ceiling, roof" were nothing more than bright white nothings. but since i was laying, i felt they had to have some physicality to them. i'm laying on the ground twitching, and in front of me, i see two figures. male, i think. they're watching me seize out indifferently. not concerned, but not malevolent, just matter of factly watching me. they're wearing what appears to be lab coats. sort of like a doctor or a scientist wears. one looked to the other and asked "....should we wake him up?", to which the other looked down at me, then looked back at him and replied "no... not yet.." the second he said that, i shot back down to my friends car at the same rate of speed i took off in, until i fell back into my body, at which rate, i nearly jumped out of my seat. i was sweaty and shaking. my friend got back into the car and asked me if i was good, and i explained what had just happened the best i could.  what really trips me out is the question "should we wake him up?".. i feel like if they would have "woken me up", then, in this realm, in this physical sense, i would of died. so it's just fascinating they used the term for me to die in this realm, as "waking up" -- i've pondered on that ever since.  "should we 'wake him up'?" -- what does this mean to you guys?   i remember it happend after i had a long talk about lucid dreaming with a friend, i didnt do anything extra...i remember that i was walking on a street and suddenly thought he wtf this is a dream..then i whent like hmmm i belief that in life imagining creates reality , so if this is a dream then imagining must definitly work here..so i thought to myself hmm what can i imagine and i decided on a old school space rocket ..so i thought about the rocket and then a loud bouldering ? sound started to roar in the enviroment and i looked up in the sky and saw this old school rocket flying over my head and i was like oh fuk it works ..then i thought hmm lets turn it into a ufo so it changed in a ufo...then i was like oh shit i can do whatever i want ..so....i thought hmm lets imagine sex :) and i walked into a house and started banging this chick and then fkng woke up hahaha   i agree that was not my story tho but i thought it was a good read... a lot of stories have these scientist dudes cheking out if we are still ok....simulation anybody...   i tend to think this life is also just a dream something u can wake up from. if that waking up means dying to this reality idk..in some of my dmt trips tho i experience a moment where i am in both (worlds) and that i have to say goodbye to my current life to move on on the other side fully aware that doing so that life will become like a dream and dissapates from my memory just as dreams do here.. it's a sad moment but acceptable..idk if that has any reality to it because well its still a dmt trip lol.. i quess someday we will see.. for now enjoy your life, and when you find yourself stressing out about whatever nonsense u think is o so important, think.. why so serious :) its all just a dream in a dream in dream anyways :)

I have also been diagnosed with ADHD for 2 years and have done a lot of research into it. adhd is a package of symptoms that can have all kinds of causes. it could be because your brain really is chronically short of dopamine. if you are often on tiktok, chances are that your lifestyle is also one of the causes. entertainment like social media, netflix, gaming are made to spike your dopamine. that's why they can be so addictive. the downside is that your tolerance for dopamine gets higher and higher as a result. so you need more and more to feel good. if on top of that you start taking adhd medication that also raises your dopamine one way or another, you can get into a very difficult situation. So I recommend going the other way first before getting diagnosed and trying medication: dopamine detox. there is plenty to find on the internet about this. and please don't make the same mistake I did by starting medication right away. if it turns out that detoxing does not help enough, you can always try the medication at a later date.

the serotonergic hallucinogens. such as LSD, ayahuasca and mushrooms seem to have more benefits than drawbacks and have begun to be taken seriously in recent years. even our more local red fly agaric has been researched and approved as a medicinal product in Canada. raw red fly agaric is poisonous. but if you neutralize the ibotenic acid, it can have positive mind-altering properties. depending on the dose, it can be sedating or induce visions. muscimol binds to the same receptors as alcohol but has quite different effects. the anticholinergic hallucinogens such as wort and mandrake are the most dangerous hallucinogens. it is possible that because the hallucinogens we have in Europe are so dangerous, it has affected our view of them throughout history. the only serotonergic hallucinogen in Sweden is probably the top plain skiing. which is fairly harmless/non-toxic. they would have drunk lemon balm tea and ginger to deal with the discomfort. but throwing up should be part of the experience. it should be cleansing. put on music maybe. maybe a little pink floyd. it depends on what you like. loreena mckennit or dead can dance is nice. music becomes more detailed and interesting on these subjects. small details more obvious. and it is said that the day after is just as pleasant. like the opposite of a hangover. too bad it didn't feel that way.

the spiritual awakening journey in alignment with the dark night of the soul and ego death is as hard to understand as actual death for our greater society. it's as mysterious. i believe what awakening can do is push you very close to schizophrenia because you become so highly aware that the reality we live in is completely constructed. there is also so much suffering and fear on this dimension that if you tap into it, it is so overwhelming that it feels like a black hole. as human beings, the superego is necessary to make sense of our identity in this world. when i first experienced ego death, i had no idea what that identity was anymore. it was all emotion, it was all fear, i genuinely didn't know what or who i was. i also was having so many realizations about how corrupt our world is and i realized that i was unable to do anything about it in a larger sense. like accepting that our dimension is too far colonized to change it. i became obsessed with waking people up and become righteously indignant about it. i was full of rage and anger but it was rooted in the sadness of the isolation of the spiritual path. there was not one person i could relate to anymore but i didn't even love or know myself - so i was unable to connect with other people because i cared so much about being spiritual and right. i surrendered and starting riding the tumultuous wake of being awake in this world. i stopped going deeper down the rabbit hole because i realized that no answer from an analytical place could bring my soul peace. i started looking towards leaders who came to earth to wake people up and became incredibly inspired because they were not filled with rage or bitterness but they were filled with god's love. i am nothing without god on this path and if i didn't have god i would not be able to move forward with the evils i have come to know about our society and the evil dimensions that coincide with our reality. there is no me, there is only an offering connected to god and i will do my best to spread god's love on earth, heal and forgive. i stopped asking questions. i look towards god for guidance. the spiritual path opened me up to a lot of evil spirits so i truly have to stand ten toes down on it. a lot of narcissistic and demonic spirits in my own family. i think of capital steez holding the bible when he jumped because he needed god too. if he stayed on the path and released his need to know, god would've found him on earth. i know god found him in death. i spent so many nights feeling so alone, i remember thinking multiple times that anyone in my position would choose to end their lives. i push through because we need more individuals who can help open up this dimension to deeper truths. there is definitely horror of knowing too much. that's really what happened. it hurt me a lot to know steez didn't finalize his mission. the message of awakening needs to be spread. rip to a very brilliant person who i consider a genius, king capital.

in psychedelic trips, not everything is the intense experience that people describe, there is a final period called "come down", in the descent you progressively go to sobriety. It is the moment in which you can already socialize with people you trust, reintegrate and reaffirm what happened on the trip, and calm down / relax mentally. it is more or less the final half of the trip. in fact, in the trance/peak you cannot follow a psychotherapy, they would do that in the descent, and at most the traditional psychedelics last up to 12 hours (the descent being a little less than half, in this case a maximum of 5-6 hours ). you can really do it with others.

"oh, i keep my coffee machine on the counter! and i keep my coffee filters near the coffee machine!"  right. because neurotypical people keep their coffee maker packed in ice inside a cooler in the garden shed, and the filters are usually placed individually between the pages of an antique encyclopedia set in the attic. self discipline.    bullsh*t... i have horrible adhd and extreme self discipline is the only way to overcome. making excuses just feeds the dragon.    yeah, i agree.  i don't use any apps other than youtube. it definitely sucks me in at times, but at least it's something that i actually learn quite a bit from, both from the videos and the chat that i get into... so at least it's not a complete waste of time.  i spent nearly 50 years not knowing i had adhd; horrible student, terrible at managing pretty much every aspect of life, the same exact problems and experiences you see the people in the videos and chat talk about, but after being diagnosed i really began digging into true "self ownership" and discipline.  it's not easy, it was completely foreign to me at first, but it's the key to living, for me at least.  it's just a matter of doing what needs to be done, when it needs to be done, regardless of whether or not i'd rather avoid it.  transcendental meditation has been helpful also, just sitting still and emptying the mind for a few minutes a day.  the brain is plastic, as science has recently discovered, and one truly can rewire one's neuropathology. it takes a lot of effort, but it's well worth it.  hey, thanks for responding and reading. i appreciate it.  i do live on the bright side. it's called the comedy and creative writing side... i guess it began as a coping mechanism in school as a 1970s kid with severe adhd. i was working with someone in april who had me do weekly self diagnostics with blueprint. while i only worked with them a short period of time they never turned the diagnostic reports off so i have just kept doing it.  i am someone that doesn't respond well to medications so following things learned here and elsewhere i got really diligent about my hrv and resting heart rate, largely through daily cardio and cold exposure.  my issues cleared up in lock step with those numbers improving. i want to get my blueprint data so i can lay the datasets over one another. i think it would make an interesting and easy to run study to give participants a strict cardio regiment and another group cardio plus daily cold plunges and see how their self reported data compares with their hrv and resting heart rate.  in any event my personal experience seems to mirror the conditions triggered in the tms trials as far as my heart rate and hrv relating to other symptoms goes. can you follow up regarding brain plasticity and bad trips? the whole idea of just how durable the changes can be has been what's kept me on the fence regarding these substances. the idea that the good changes are somewhat permanent sounds great. the idea you might have to face some challenges is an acceptable risk. the concern over semi permanent negative changes scares the hell out of me.   fwiw i've made my iphone grayscale and nightshift all the time, deleted almost all apps, the ones i kept are in folders so i have to be intentional about what i am opening and why. it's made a night and day difference for me.

What this video reports is not logical, deaths from drugs cocaine does not represent even 3% in the United States, medical reports for cocaine use are minimal in all countries and despite being a stimulant drug it has not even been calculated a dose that can be considered an overdose. I do not defend this drug but the easiest way to prevent people from consuming it is by warning them that cocaine is not what they have always wanted us to believe, cocaine is a stealthy drug with no effects that acts in synergy with other stimuli and depends of each person's body, how it reacts with the drug, it's like people who drink half a glass of alcohol or a bottle and are already drunk, it's the same with cocaine, many people will swear that they go crazy with that drug, but most of them don't care. for strong effects. The real effect of cocaine on most organisms in normal doses is a minimal increase in energy and attention, that is, if you are sleepy and you take a few passes of cocaine, you will continue to be sleepy, you will simply endure sleep a little more, the The increase in energy is like having a coffee and the effects last between 10-15 minutes and the increase in heart rate is for 10-20 minutes and it is very little, if you jog or walk fast you will have the same increase in heart rate and not That's why you're going to die, that's why cocaine is a drug that hardly leads to death even if it can intoxicate your body and kill you very slowly without realizing it. Cocaine is a stimulant and it will depend on your mental stability, you know that physiologically it does not have considerable effects, now cocaine will always find a place in your mind to settle in, that is to say, it settles in with alcohol, an easy example if you are going to present yourself in front of to people and you are nervous you get some good passes and manage to overcome that stressful situation every time you are in similar situations the mind will ask you for cocaine, if you are drunk and thanks to the cocaine you are sober again the body will ask you for cocaine, if you are Driving drowsy and taking coke passes along the way, your mind will always ask you for it. If you have anxiety due to a stressful situation and you rely on cocaine, your mind will ask you for it later. Cocaine is a drug that you should not try because it will always find a place to settle in your life, physically it does not give you anything, its effects are minimal, if you want quality cocaine and flavor the prices are high and in general it is a very different drug than what the media including this video have led us to believe.

i only had them once and not as large a dose as i would have chosen but it marked a turning point in my life.  from them i learned in a first hand way that a self exists seperate from the mind and that the latter is more a symptom or emergent phenomenon that is mutable changeable and at times out of sync with who we are. who we really are.  its like (conceptually) putting on glasses for the first time or having double vision and correcting it, but also the reverse in some ways of things we've integrated and run on autopilot that we ought to step back and reconsider from a new perspective.  integration and disintegration. freedom from all the blocks and chains we box ourselves into. all the ruts and wagons and loops we get stuck in. all of how we see things, that we think is everything, as we step back and zoom out and see more its like oh. its not that these issues are less per se they just aren't the whole picture and i guess now that i see more of it i suppose proportionally they really are not as big a deal as i thought. we just try so hard to get other people to see us or feel as strongly as we do for them to take what we feel seriously that we get our sense of identity all buggered up into it but sometimes its as simple as taking your head and turning it a different direction and just like that everything changes forever

i made an attempt to get a script for it but i was denied by medicaid.   mine doesn't. i was denied. it's the legal drug trade that most don't see it for. i think add or adhd is a bullshit diagnosis that we as a society use as justification to self medicate. schools are teaching every child the same curriculum. they're overlooking dozens of strengths that these children have by focusing on a few  weaknesses. they should be tested at a young age and make the number one priority, to engage them directly into careers which involve all of their strengths. of course we as humans need to be sedated in order to give a shit about things that don't really matter. for example, as a kid i hated math. still i know how to count money and balance my finances. i used to argue that it was all i'll ever need to know in life as far as math is concerned. turns out, i was 100% correct lol it's now been normalized to basically give children meth in a pill form. i'm sure that lack of it has lead many into meth addiction after first using it to cope with their adderall withdrawals. because let's keep it real if you run out of your medication, it's because you over medicated. makes sense though as you had built up a tolerance and now needed more. when is enough, enough? people will say to stop using it. i have for over a year. the whole time, feeling super unmotivated. foggy. so i went back on it and use it. idk the answer. i do know that withdrawal symptoms can lead to someone mercilessly beating the shit out of the next man that steps out of line.

this is so incredibly exciting. psychedelics will revolutionize mental health. i plan to be on the front lines of this effort in a legal and therapeutic context in the near future. it is brave of you to bring this information to light. even though both psilocybin and mdma have received breakthrough therapy designation from the fda (stronger support than the covid vaccines), there is still an unwarranted stigma because of decades of propaganda and disinformation from those in power. that stigma is being reversed swiftly, and it won't be long til this necessary body of science receives it's long awaited designation as a legitimate psychotherapeutic treatment.  ibogaine for example cures severe addiction  and even erases symptoms of opioid withdrawal. these are modern marvels that far surpass outcomes of current mental health treatment, and it's about damn time we all take a look at the science.   i have a question. do you trust science? even though we've all been subjected to decades of politically charged disinformation on this topic, it is a fact that psilocybin and mdma have both received breakthrough therapy designation from the fda (more scientific backing than even the covid vaccine) and they are on track to become a bigger breakthrough in mental health treatment than cbt. we are living in strange times. it's only makes sense to trust what science is telling us, which is that psychedelics can cure severe mental illness with greater efficacy than even the best studied psychiatric medications. see if you can find a treatment for smoking cessation with greater evidence than psilocybin.

in my opinion, the sentiment expressed in this video is rather naive.  "magic mushrooms" are not all simply cubensis.  in fact those who really know about them, would know that there are vastly more potent strains.  in fact, wildly-popular species psilocybe cubensis he talks about in this video isn't particularly potent compared to say panaeolus cyanescens or panaeolus tropicalis, both of which are at least 3x the potency and often closer to 5x or 6x the potency on a per-dried-gram basis of cubensis.  and those aren't even the strongest out there!  some of these cold-weather wood-loving species that you'd find out west while hiking like psilocybe azurescens are even stronger sometimes if the weather conditions are right.  my point is that to talk about "magic mushrooms" in the sense he is really is not advised because various species and sometimes even within the same species vary so much in overall potency and even relative ratios of active component compounds (and there are three primaries - psilocybin, the relatively stable prodrug to psilocin, and baeocystin).  instead, extreme caution should be considered taking any psychoactive mushroom.  and if you do take them, just know eventually you will get your ass handed to you one time.  that's the nature of them, and no one i've ever met who has taken them for any length of time avoids a bad trip eventually.  i suppose such people exist, but they are rare unless they've only dabbled with them.  instead, bad trips are real, absolutely horrific, and to be expected eventually even while they can be among the most valuable learning experiences possible.  and, further, if you are prone to psychosis, mood disorders like bipolar disorder, schizophrenia, or similar mental disorders or such a disorder runs in your family you probably should avoid not only mushrooms but all psychedelics (a case can be made for depression, though, that mushrooms could be valuable in helping those who suffer from it).  note that right now, the psychedelic studies out there are, by and large, screening against most mental disorders prior to allowing one to even participate in the study, so this advice is being heeded by the professionals too.  i have a libertarian view about drugs and really think we should regulate, not forbid, most usually-termed "illicit" drugs, but just know that magic mushrooms contain very powerful substances not to be taken lightly regardless of their legal status.  and for the love of god, please do not try them your first time at a party!  except in the case of very low dosages, these aren't really very good as "party drugs" to be honest because things can, and often do, go horribly wrong in that kind of socially-complex setting.

just because one experiences, perceives, feels, or believes something during a psychedelic experience, that doesn't mean it's true.  that is the case for the entities, which do not exist outside of our minds, and it's also the case for non-duality, unless one interprets non-duality in a way that is consistent with what we already know about matter and humans from physics, biology, psychology, and sociology.  however, i couldn't agree more with this:  psychedelics are a wonderful shovel for personal development.    just because some mystics have believed something for thousands of years doesn't make it true either. so, is non- duality true?  it depends on what we mean by it, i,e,  how  we define it.  let's go by the definition of the wonderful host of this youtube channel (whose name i apologize for not knowing how to spell). quoting from this video:  you do not exist as a self.  the self  who you are  is an illusion.  if you actually remember who you are, you are not a human being at all; [you're] something else.   now, whether that is true depends on how we interpret it.  if it's interpreted as saying that our narratives about our motivations are usually illusions, and that most of what makes us who/what we are is hidden in our unconscious, then that is probably true, and it's something that most psychologists would agree with.  but if it's taken literally, then it would violate physics and probably is untrue. thank you for explaining your view.   i think a cow's consciousness and my consciousness are largely of the same kind, except for some capabilities  like deliberation, thinking, and language  that cows lack, as well as different desires and sensations; for example, seeing a field of grass doesn't water my mouth and seeing an ox or cow doesn't turn me on.   i think both consciousnesses are products of natural selection. the similarities in the bodies, brains, genes, and behaviors support the hypothesis of the similarity of consciousnesses.  all of this is consistent with biology.     by the way, for me, consciousness is material, i.e., it's an emergent property of complexly organized matter (neurons, synapses, etc.).  so, i see no reason why (in future) a sufficiently complex computer program or piece of human-made hardware cannot be conscious; except it's going to lack many human and animal sensations (like pain, jealousy, and the desire to pasture in a field of grass).    psychedelics are still illegal in most jurisdictions, and this is a public forum.  here's an alternative approach:   when ideas are being discussed, focus on the ideas rather than the speaker.  i am not the subject of this discussion. the truth and falsity of my statements can be assessed independently of who or what i am, unless i were speaking about myself, which i was not.  accepting an idea only if the person who speaks it is credible will lead one into error.

it's important to note that there are many different versions of becoming "awakened".  i got slapped in the face by many of them in ways that are just undeniable. i started going down the road of wanting to learn more about it all. (which really knowledge has always been my driving force even pre spiritual curiosity stuff entered my life.) then parts of my mind started whispering to me that we've been down those roads many times over. gained the knowledge and the powers that come with it. they even showed me some of them. (just minor stuff about control over the body mostly.) there's even been some other stuff though. nothing that can't be explained away as random occurrence or cognitive bias.   now mostly those parts of me  are just like, "all of this stuff gets boring after awhile, it's also exhausting getting the knowledge and powers. we'd rather just let go and cease being."  it's not a depressive message either really, it's more of a feeling of release.  i talked to a buddhist teacher briefly about those voices for a lack of a better term and his response was so simple. they are probably left over remnants from prior lives and that i should listen to the ones that seem the most wise.  the wisest ones seem to be the most compassionate ones and also the ones that advocate the most for just sitting, ceasing to engage in the world as much as possible and to slowly fade away... in the most joyous way possible by finding joy in more and more simple things until you find joy in nothingness.  this is why i have no motivation. at least in the material realm. why bother when i can sometimes get the most joy and happiness i've ever had by just paying attention to the breath while sitting or laying down? i can't help but yawn in boredom and exhaustion at the idea energy work. i learned how to do it in seconds. i've made my vibration go through the roof. probably even managed to emit physical light.  a few months after playing around with that stuff parts of me started waking back up i guess you could say. they were all like, "we've been here before. we've had the ability to do all of the things that you have ever wanted to do. we are pretty over them. we'd rather sit and slowly cease to exist by letting go."  and funny thing is that indeed, i get the most joy from sitting and letting go of all desires and just being moment to moment.  even is the only thing that has managed to actually fix major depression... which i found out was caused by unmet desires that i had absolutely no desire to do the things necessary to get the desires fulfilled.... but i sure as heck felt like i was supposed to want to do those things. i recommend you look into theravada buddhism. specifically the thai forest tradition. it strips out the religous aspects mostly and is more about well, realizing that craving or relying on pleasure from anything material is unwise. and is about detachment and renunciation. it mostly focuses on the pleasure of mediation... at least at first. the further stages come naturally later.  there is some really good teaching on here. all the teachers are called ajahn... bhram is a good start. pair down your spending. save a few thousand dollars. figure out some career that is very non demanding and very part time.. and yes lower paid.  and move somewhere cheaper... do it as part of saving money. move into shared housing now.  the pleasures of the physical world utterly pale in comparison to the pleasure of the mental (or if you want, the spiritual world.) once you realize this and that you can have the most pleasure you've ever had on tap whenever you want it, the physical for the most part becomes useless beyond a means to sustain the body at a bare minimum healthy way.  .. the catch for me is that having joy on tap got boring.  but hey, that's one great reason to meditate and why i got into buddhism. false. stop victim blaming!  you can indeed decide how to react to external circumstances. however, the fact is that modern day jobs and society are utterly screwed up and are the cause of stress and illnesses.  it's extremely hard for most people to remove themselves from it. this means that you are not at fault for not being able to control your stress levels. it's near impossible when you are constantly want to reenter the fray and that is totally ok.

you can't really do autism vs adhd they both run on a spectrum and everyone has different symptoms and experiences with each. a lot of the symptoms overlap some people with adhd don't like new experiences and unfamiliarity while others do and the same goes for autism some of them do like new experiences and unfamiliarity. i'm not trying to be disrespectful. i'm just saying this vs that just can't be done with these conditions. i am both autistic and adhd. witch my experience of having both is different from everyone else. i personally hate unfamiliarity, but it's more complicated than that because some places even peoples houses i don't know, i will just immediately feel comfortable there even if i don't know the people or meeting them for the first time. and then some places it's the total opposite. i have no idea why my brain does this it's so strange it doesn't bother me though. this same thing goes for people too, some people i'm more drawn to than others for no particular reason. there are 2 sides to autism from my experience either they hate being touched or the love affection. i am on the love affection side but i can't just get it from anyone it has to be certain people that i'm immediately more drawn to. my brain is very selective like that. yet again this just happens without reason. (and no i don't mean sexual attraction that's a different feeling than what i'm talking about. i'm taking comfortability with a person). another thing for me is i like new experiences, not love, but like. i love learning about new things and the fact i have autism is the best because my mind is so open and i can understand very complex things. simple things on the other hand are quite difficult. i over think everything, i will say i have made massive improvements with that. but that is a symptom of both autism and adhd same with hyperactivity is a symptom of both. not all people with adhd have the h part so they just call it add. anyway this is just my take on this. i don't mean to be rude or say you're wrong because you're not wrong it's just the symptoms you point out can be symptoms of both autism and adhd. it's not one or the other. both conditions are linked to each other biologicaly. so if you have one you are vary likely to have the other or develop it later in life witch can happen.

still blaming a little 10yo girl for disrupting his dinners when she was thrown to the ground and hit!!!!! never considering that i was reacting/defending against daily abuse, or was in fact impaired by adhd or autism or ptsd!! it's bizarre!!!!!  to this day it's hard getting treatment because if i try to explain the situation of the layered, multiplicity of horrors i experienced fairly early it sounds like i'm- and i quote from shitty low-quality therapists- "all over the place". i have to explain it extremely carefully and strategically right off the bat. i can't make one mistake!!!!  aaaaaarrrrrrrgh i hate stupid people!!!!!  the good news is that, society is already getting better as the boomer genertion slowly dies off- i can see it happening before my eyes. people think their sick narcissistic perversities are outdated, out of touch and irrelevant. some are reacting to their ruining society with covid paranoia in effort to protect only them. bad news is they keep reporting my "okay boomer" comments ive made for years on this account as spam so i might lose this youtube account soon. good news: it's not the end of the world and i have another one.

when i was 13 i was spending the night at a friend's place with another buddy of mine. his parents were gone so we procured some keyboard duster, the poor man's nitrous (think they put an irritant in it now so you can't do this any more). there was a new litter of kitten so we had a bunch of cats running around as we inhaled the duster. my buddy took a huge pull off it and his voice got way way deeper than i knew anyone's voice could go as he said "oh fuuuuuuck!" sitting on the couch he grabbed a kitten in each hand and was squeezing them a little too tight, all the while staring straight ahead with wide eyes and a slack jaw coupled with a look of scared amazement. we started yelling at him to let go of the kttens without a response. a few seconds went by and i thought he'd snap out of it since it doesn't last too long, but he just kept staring ahead totally unresponsive. he eventually came back to reality. his first words were "i just saw god!" he then told us that none of this is what we think it is and how "reality isn't real!" this was well before things like trip reports and it was even before the matrix came out, so the idea of this place being fake or a simulation wasn't widespread and common like it is now.   no matter how much he said i just dismissed it as just the keyboard duster messing with his brain, but now i think that for some reason the stuff shot him out of his body like what dmt does. if i had to guess one of the triggers for a spirit to separate the from the body is lack of oxygen to the brain and he kinda fooled the process with huffing that stuff, assuming things like spirits, god and an afterlife do exist.   allow me to add that under no circumstances should anyone inhale keyboard duster or anything like that. it can all kill you very easily or cause very serious, permanent brain damage. even though i didn't think his story was anything but a delusion i still never did that garbage again nor anything like it. so please, don't try to use chemicals you pick up at wal-mart like that. it's not worth the risk to maybe see god and come back, because if you do enough for that to happen it may be a one way trip. i've known two people that actually died from similar things. it can happen.

no rather the other way around, 1d-lsd is about 75% as potent as lsd-25, which is why it is sold in 150ug blotter.   that it has a more intense effect or some think it has a more intense effect is because the lsd-25 cardboard boxes almost never have the dose for which they are sold. the average in america was ~60-70ug per box, which isn't much (although they were sold as 100-150ug). if you then suddenly consume 150ug 1d-lsd, ergo more than 100ug lsd-25, then it is clear that it has a more intense effect. chemically speaking, 1d-lsd isn't as potent as lsd-25, so one should look at the factors that lead some to perceive it as more intense.   yes, same as lsd-25. for some it seems more intense, for others weaker, there are so many factors involved. but to say that 1d-lsd is more intense than lsd-25 is not correct.

for an idealized but still useful vision of healthy parenting (setting the cheesy jokes aside), you may want to watch family ties from the 80s. it's on pluto tv.   set aside the forced humor it's actually a beautiful view of how a loving family treats each other. if you've never had that it may be nice to see.   sometimes my family was pleasant and nice but other times, or some of the other members, were verbally abusive, maliciously critical and unkind for no reason. so i didn't end up with the most abusive history by any means, but definitely was treated like dirt far too often and my emotional or personal needs routinely ignored or belittled. sometimes my parents handled their problems maturely and appropriately and other times they didn't. i did receive some good examples and basic training in increasing responsibilities, but in some areas where they really should have got off their ass emotionally and showed guidance they did not. its definitely held me back in life but at least now in my early 40s i'm starting to feel like i'm finally catching up. i probably would have been able to "catch up" sooner if it were not for some tough extended situations in my 20s and 30s, some, unfortunately, also a direct result of them, though some not. for an idealized but still useful vision of healthy parenting (and setting the cheesy laugh tracks aside), people may want to watch a show call family ties from the 80s. (it's on pluto tv for those who stream and probably nf tho i can't vouch for that). setting aside the forced jokes, it's actually a beautiful view of how a loving, responsible, caring family treats each other. for those who have never had that it may be nice to see represented in a fictionalized way. it's never too late to seek better emotional health. i too struggle with a mix of "trauma brain" and adhd symptoms. while we each have to do our own work with our personal issues, i can recommend one thing for our adhd symptoms - neurofeedback. i've done it limitedly in the past and i felt i received a significant improvement from it. it's been over ten years now and i plan to go back soon for a full second protocol. other than meds, i feel it's the most effective adhd support out there. you may wish to consider it.

i very much enjoy what you have to say about all of this andres. i find the models you're explaining here very fascinating.   one model i've always held for the difference between 5-meo-dmt, nn-dmt, and other psychedelics is like having a light source, and then shining that light source through a kaleidoscope, and then the eye of the observer on the other side sees through this. so there are really three components to any experience, in addition to the depth of the trajectory through that experience.   most psychedelics play with a certain amount of the light that comes through the perceptual kaleidoscope and is reflected outward to the eye of the observer. on lsd and psilocybin for example you can start looking at these patterns coming through into ordinary space and gradually push yourself into low-dose dmt spaces by approaching the kaleidoscope. but experiences like dmt take your eye right up to and through the kaleidoscope where you see the source of light (energy/information) being fragmented into all these colorful patterns and shapes. you can work your way through the perceptual kaleidoscope on high doses of dmt and start to approach the source of the light, but it's always through this lens that you seem to travel. however, on 5-meo-dmt you have gone beyond the kaleidoscope, except maybe on low enough doses, and you have entered into the source of the light itself and are not interacting with gestalts of information instead of the reflections and transformations of that information in the kaleidoscopic dmt space.   at a certain point all experiences approach this unifying light or source of information, but 5-meo-dmt puts you there very readily. on dmt it takes work to get anywhere near that, and you still never get as far as you will on higher doses of 5-meo.   the thing that defines the dmt experience i think is the "walls" of the kaleidoscope that the experience is happening within. there are no walls outside of that where the source of light is coming from in 5-meo. instead it might be like a filament, or whatever is producing the light that you start to interact with when you work with the deeper substrata of the experience. but on dmt, the deeper you go you either approach this light and hit the back of the mirror, or you bump up against one of the walls. i think it's possible to exit the other side of the kaleidoscope on dmt and actually enter into the light, but this might require some focused coordination and a very high dose.
