if you ever do dmt, please don't expect  'jesus christ' to meet you at the doorstep, no matter how much you pray or believe. i've heard of trips where jesus comes to them as an evil demon; what say you that? don't trust an idol, trust in yourself. dark remus i agree to a point but ketamine? i suppose it's addictive properties and the usual method of use is harmful to the bladder etc (insufflation), but i've always had a good time with it, even a deeper 'spiritual' time if you will. it's ability to render you into these insane spaces etc. although saying that, you mention 'lsd' as 'more angelic' drug, but from my experience of peoples actual use, it happens to be that specific mix of lsd and ketamine (often with some uppers chucked in cos it'll be a festival or something), that has melted a few of my mates brains seemingly permanently. to me the 'demon' drugs though are just the opiates, benzos, alcohols, solvents etc.   that's a great goal! even though i'm not religious (in any conventional sense), myself, i entirely understand your point, and your fears.  i would just say don't ever write it off - we don't know if we only get one chance to live our individual lives, and i often think it's sad that most people go from the cradle to the yawning grave without ever giving these things a go. psychedelic experiences are often the single most important events of peoples lives; the second time i smoked dmt it changed my life forever in unspeakably brilliant (and yet often terrifying) ways. only a portion of our species have the bravery to take the plunge and i appreciate that some (especially the mentally ill or generally fragile minded), would do well to stay away. it's like a trip through heaven and hell and then back to the cosmic womb. it's even been used to help terminally ill patients come to terms with impending death, because at high enough doses it essentially 'replicates' the 'death experience' in the sense that your brain goes into panic mode thinking it's dying, and then you surrender to it and enter a dimension beyond your comprehension.   haha, my god i don't know, i've told the story in several levels of detail online but i don't like to 'give it all away' if you understand me. but lets just say it involved me thinking i'd died, and then being transported to a 'extremely familiar' 'place' that was hard to bear. my first thought upon being back there (it was a kind of purgatorial space involving different coloured clouds), was 'oh my god i already knew all this why why why did i ever want to come back here' - as if i'd re-entered somewhere i'd been for infinities.  then there was a portion that felt like i was in the deep sea - like the abyssal zone in our oceans - an extreme yet kind of comfortable sense of pressure surrounded me. extreme peace. ultimate rest. then suddenly i noticed these 'entities'  - self-transforming, endlessly beautiful conscious mandalas, that extended 'arms' out into my brain, inducing a sense of extreme orgasm, beyond anything i have ever experienced in the 'real world'.  that's all i'm really willing to say, although i'll finish with adding that it felt like the only 'real' experience i'd ever had, and that worldly mundane life is kind of dreamy and vague in comparison. like how life is compared to a normal dream. it felt hyper-real, beyond real, extremely intensely real in a way i never thought could even be experienced. anyway, i ramble. but do perhaps think about trying it sometime, especially if you really want to know 'the truth'. just know that 'the truth' is both the most blissful amazing thing possible, and also, at the very same time, the most hellish evil despicable thing possible. the ode 'be careful what you wish for' comes to mind. to be inundated with unconscious 'truth' is to kind of 'finish the game' so to speak. i almost feel like a 'hacker' in the simulation, or some such similar gibberish, after that experience. as if, if life were truly a game, i was given a (albeit physically and mentally expensive) 'cheat code'.   cheers for the response! was just rambling tbh lol. i will definitely check out this chap's youtube channel; i always enjoy reading or watching stuff about near-death-experiences, or just everything from visionary states to psychotic states etc. been fun talking, i'm a sucker for rambling on when it comes to this subject, and for sure you're right - 'be careful what you align with', as you put it.   my god, i can't thank you enough! listening to this last night freaked me out because of how accurate it was, or appeared to be. i'm about half way through. it seems insanely similar to my own experiences. you become the entirety of everything you have ever said, done, or thought, and all is revealed. this happened to me. i really cannot thank you enough beautiful internet stranger; you have helped to remind me that love is the centre of all things, and as one ventures further out from the source and into the outer darkness, they become 'changed'; gargoylian, demonic etc, but not essentially 'evil', just 'broken', and that it is a gradation; there are infinite forms and spaces between the two polar extremes of ''heaven and hell'. the fact i encountered a very scary fear-inducing, hell-like portion during the trip i've been relaying to you, really hit home. i'm rambling again, but it feels important - you are one amongst a very small handful of internet strangers that have really helped move me along and down the path, and elucidated things that were previously hidden.  you are clearly a very intelligent and wise person to notice the distinct correlations between what i wrote to you, and what the person you linked me to experienced, to the point it is almost terrifying. thank you so much, and i hope you live a long and fulfilling infinity! : )   well i snorted it everyday for a good year or so back when it was pure, also did it on and off over other periods. i do have some mild bladder related problems, and a friend of mine who went through similar levels of ketamine abuse has really bad digestive problems nowadays as a result (this was in our late teens to mid 20s, we're all in our mid 30s now).  so who really knows - i know a lot of people that do it regularly always say to blow your nose a lot and not snort it too 'deep'. but tbh, the safest and apparently the best route to a full on k-hole is using the liquid and injecting it im (as in, in any muscular or fatty area of the body). but i'm not one for injecting recreational drugs lol. definitely entirely removes the possible bladder problems you might experience with prelonged use though   lol that makes it sound horrible but nah i mean im not iv - anyone can administer it, doesn't require any medical skill like iving something does. but yeah, for recreational ketamine use at high doses, im is the way to go in terms of doing as little harm as possible to your body over a prolonged period.  but generally from what i know you need someone else there to inject it otherwise you run the risk of being semi-conscious or unconscious before you've removed the needle

mir aber ''ach!..du hast jetzt noch dieses baggie voll shrooms und das ballerst du auch noch weg''..leider waren das schon relativ viele..ich hatte darin 4g (trocken) und im kuhlschrank hatte ich noch 5g nasse, eingelegte magische truffel und eine groe sanpedro kaktus-spitze..ich wollte an dem abend also die trockenen 4g pilze nehmen und vorher kam noch ein freund vorbei, der mir noch mal 5g (trocken) vorbeibrachte und sie in die selbe tute tat, wo meine 4g (trocken) drin waren..was ich leider nicht mitbekommen habe..als dieser freund dann sater wieder verschwunden war und ich ganz allein bei mir war, beschloss ich das ganze baggie mit den trockenen pilzen darin mit einmal einzuwerfen und dazu noch 2g truffel..ich wusste nur leider nicht dass in diesem baggie statt 4g (trocken), jetzt insgesamt 9g (trocken) enthalten waren..sie sahen auch nur aus wie 4g..komsicherweise war das volumen in der tute so gering, dass ich niemals gedacht hatte, dass es 9g (trocken) sein konnten..aber egal..ich a alle pilze aus der tute und noch 2g truffel (nass) dazu und wartete bis endlich die wirkung eintrat..das schlimme ist, zu der zeit war mein hochstma an pilzen was ich vertrug insgesamt 4g nass und ich a mit einmal 11g trockene pilze, ohne etwas zu ahnen..ahnungslos wie ich war, dachte ich es waren nur maximal 6g..dann begannen sie zu wirken..ich fuhlte mich irgendwie schon ziemlich schnell, extrem komisch und bekam auch gleich ein sehr ekliges gefuhl im magen und dazu negative gedanken, so als ob mich irgendwas schlimmes erwartet..ich hatte leichte angst und suchte nach meinen baldrian-kapseln bzw. pilzstoppern..ich konnte sie nirgends finden, denn ich hatte keine mehr, jedoch dachte ich mir zu dem zeitpunkt noch so ''ach was soll's''..setzte mich wieder hin und versuchte mich abzulenken, was mir nicht gelang..ich began daruber nachzudenken, dass ich bei meiner suche nach dem baldrian bzw. pilzstoppern garkeine tute mit den 5g zauberpilzen (trocken), die mir mein freund zuvor vorbeigebracht hatte, in meinem schubfach vorfand und dann wurde mir klar, was er zu mir nebenbei gesagt hatte..es blitzte in meinem unterbewusstsein auf, wie flashbacks..'''ach!..du hast ja hier schon ein tutchen mit pilzen darin..ich tue sie dir einfach dazu''..ich schreckte innerlich auf und bekam ziemliche angst, weil mir nun klar wurde, dass ich insgesamt 11g (9g trocken zauberpilze und 2g nasse zaubertruffel) intus hatte..''was soll' ich jetzt machen?..ich werde sicher durchdrehen'' dachte ich..mein herz fing an schwer zu schlagen und ein riesiger klo bildete sich in meinem hals..mir fiel ein, ich habe noch sehr starkes, klebriges, kristallines cannabis-staub-konzentrat in einem kleinen gefa, neben dem bong..''das wird mich beruhigen, dachte ich so bei mir''..nichts hatte weiter von der wahrheit weg sein konnen..wie konnte ich nur so dumm sein..ich rauchte einen dicken kopf davon und der schlimmste alptraum meines lebens begann..ich bekam herzrasen wie noch nie, der schwei lief mir in niagarafallen aus allen poren, ich zitterte am ganzen korper, hatte todesangst, mein hals schnurte sich immer weiter zu, mir wurde total schwindelig und kotzubel, nur konnte ich mich nicht ubergeben und meine gliedmaen wurden zu brei..ich konnte nicht aufstehen und lag hilflo da..bestenfalls konnte ich mich gerade so hochziehen, in eine halbe sitzposition..ich konnte nicht sprechen und klar denken, alles was ich ansah wirkte bedrohlich und lebensgefahrlich..ich konnte nichtmal auf die toilette gehen..ich habe irgendwie auf den tappig gemacht..''ich werde sterben und/oder wahnsinnig werden und den rest meines lebens in einer anstalt verbringen'', dachte ich..das ganze kam dann so weit, dass ich in panische, sich immer wieder von vorne abspielende bewegungsmuster verfiel..ich konnte mich dagegen nicht erwehren..es war so unglaublich schlimm..ich dachte, ''jeden moment belibt mein herz stehen, oder ich werde wahnsinnig''..dann plotzlich auf dem peak, da fingen meine finger- und zehenspitzen gleichzeitig an zu kribbeln wie verruckt..so als ob ich stundenlang draufgesessen hatte..dann meine unterschenkel und unterarme..dann meine oberschenkel und oberarme..und dann kribbelte schlielich mein gesamter korper..ich dachte nur ''jetzt ist es so weit..jetzt habe ich einen schlaganfall und sterbe ganz allein in meiner wohnung..ich habe es verdient!''..dann verabschiedete ich mich gedanklich von allem was ich auf dieser welt liebte und von dem ich zwar nicht glaubte dass es mich auch liebt, aber hoffte dass es das trotzdem irgendwie tat und verlor das bewusstsein vollstandig in einem riesigen white-out..ich hatte mich vollstandig aufgelot..ich habe keine ahnung was dann geschah..ich wachte auf und der trip war irgendwie vorbei..ich schaute auf die uhr und es war 5 stunden nach der einnahme..ich merkte immernoch dass ich mich ganz leicht trippy fuhlte, aber das schlimmste war voruber..ich war irgendwie froh das uberlebt zu haben, doch irgendwas sagte mir, dass ich es nicht wirklich uberlebt habe und die sache noch nicht druchgestanden ist..und ich sollte recht behalten..etwas ist in dieser nacht ist in mir gestorben..und es kehrte nie zuruck..ich hatte von nun an ein standiges gefuhl der angst in meinem bauch..was ich auch tat, ich konnte mich nicht wohl fuhlen..immer war ich in sorge..ich konnte auch nicht mehr kiffen, was zu der zeit fur mich wirklich sehr schlimm war, denn ich war ja die 8 jahre davor stark cannabis abhangig..jedesmal wenn ich nun versuchte einen bong zu rauchen, bekam ich so heftige panik-attacken und flash-backs, dass mein kreislauf schlielich kollabierte und ich zitternd und bewusstlos am boden lag..auch andere substanzen, egal welcher art gaben mir starke angstgefuhle und unwohlsein bishin zum kollaps..von da an sollten depersonalisation und derealisation meine stundigen begleiter sein..auch eine sehr starke version der hppd stellte sich eine woche danach ein und war nun stetig an meiner seite..  10 jahre ist das jetzt her..die hppd und die dp/dr habe ich 3 jahre nach dem vorfall besiegt..jedoch kehrt die depersonalisation/derealisation noch hin und wieder in stresssituatinen zuruck und angstzustande hatte ich seit dem immer mal wieder..ich hatte ein ernste ptsd entwickelt..das trieb mich zu beruhigungsmitteln wie kratom, um meine angst etwas besser in den griff zu bekommen..leider wurde ich darauf allergisch und irgendwann fing ich dann an h zu nehmen..heute kampfe ich gegen meine sucht..ich bin ruiniert (:3)   ob ich wohl jemals nochmal lsd nehmen sollte?..konnte mir das uberhaupt nochmaal was gutes bringen?..

datura🌼 had me rolling🤣 2:20 🚬 was brutal   i'm glad i am done with that habit.   to answer your first question of how hard it was to quit is subjective. in terms of mental difficulty it was a 6/10 annoying but manageable. everyone's experience is different but it is possible to be done well if you slowly change.   the way i quit it was lowering dosage of nicotine over time and associating it with bad flavors. so find cheap nasty flavors and you will not want it anymore eventually.   i will say though i went on the vaping path for a while with juul. i was done with cigarettes but i made a bad choice trying a vape.   it was somewhat harder  to quit for me since the dosage of nicotine was higher then i was used to. so i had lower the dosage over time , endure the headaches and irritability of the cravings but the nasty flavor of the burnt coils and bad juice flavor made me eventually give it up.    good luck and hopefully you don't have a high tolerance to nicotine yet.  the biggest factors are dosage and longevity of the habit. stop it early and it will be easier.

i sure would like to know where the heck _psilocybe cyanescens_ is from. what sort of habitat? hell, what *continent?*  in the pacific northwest of the usa, which is a popular guess as to origins, it grows in wood chip beds, near wood chip beds in old lawns where the clippings have been left -- and in invasive beach grasses from europe, and in disturbed roadside areas on the oregon and washington coasts, in close proximity to other invasive eurasian plants -- being himalayan blackberry and scotch broom.  i'll believe the pacific northwest story if someone can show me a documented case of it being found in a pnw wilderness area. as far as i know it never has been found away from human disturbance, usually on hardwood or douglas fir wood chips (and it _really_ likes red alder).   similar situation in europe -- landscaping with wood chips, mostly.   makes me think its native habitat went away at the end of the last glacial period. maybe it's from beringia, where it made a living in drainages on the southern, moderate pacific beach glacial refugia -- drainages with lots of alder driftwood, all busted up by big pacific storms. if so, it must've held on somewhere until wood chips came along ... or maybe it didn't? could spores be preserved in ice or permafrost for 10,000 years or so? i'm guessing that's possible, maybe.   all wild speculation straight out of me arse, but interesting to think about.   this video reminded me of the topic because i recalled a quick, sort of throwaway speculation i heard once in a video from allan rockefeller, where he wondered out loud if _ps. cyanescens_ might not actually be from australia. i don't know if he has any sort of evidence for that.   i guess one should consider the locations of its closest relatives -- which are, iirc, _ps. allenii,_ _ps. azurescens,_ (another mysterious _psilocybe_ ) and _ps. subaeruginosa?_

i had night terrors as a child, insanely detailed and frightening nightmares. around the age of 7 or 8 i had my first lucid dream. whenever i'd become aware i was dreaming i'd do something to wake myself up like jump through a window or off a cliff.  during my early twenties i realized that i could do more thsn just wake myself up. i could control what happened in my dreams. i did quite a bit of flying. it's an incredible feeling. i got to tbe point i was lucid dreaming every single night until i was visited by what looked like a garden gnome. he stood about to my knees, had a blue suit, red cap and white beard. it said "you're not supposed to be doing this". since i thought it was just in my head i slapped it across the face and just took off flying.   after that night the lucid dreams stopped, so maybe the gnome wasn't just in my head. i hear from a lot of astral projection stories that people will be told that they're not allowed to do what they're doing, and some think that dreaming puts us in the astral, so it seems as if there's something that doesn't want us being anything more than just earthbound meat machines. i think i should also mention that along with the night terrors i'm pretty sure i had some obes st that age as well, and i don't think the gnome was the first thing to visit me while i was asleep in my dreams. as far back as i can recall i've had what seems like some kind of overlay in my field of vision. it looks like the snow on an old tv without any signal, except it's not black and white but in color. when i close my eyes i being to see faces and geometric patterns appearing from the "snow". they look pretty much the same as many of the simulated dmt trips and pictures i've seen. i had my first lucid dream at about the 7 and i've had experiences while sober that defy explanation, too numerous to list here. i'm of the opinion that it is possible to enter the dmt space without exogenous dmt. i also think the experience would be easier to handle and maybe even be guided. if there's any truth to any of this spirituality stuff i think that's the way to go and could be our next step. there's nothing wrong with using dmt but i don't think we have to do it that way.

very interesting. yep i believe so. i used to have many instances of this from my teens thru my early 30s or later 20s. i can recall many times i became drowsy or sleepy during the day when i didn't want to. it would probably be more likely if i got less sleep than ideal the night before but it's as you say, also happened when i felt generally rested or alert.   i won't say it always happened but every time i had to sit still for any length of time there was a possibility it could happen.  sometimes i could quickly shake it off and sometimes i couldn't. i couldn't predict when they would happen. i began to think i might have low-level narcolepsy bec these casual sleepiness attacks would frequently come on with no warning.   now that i'm 40+ i can't say i've noticed them as much. it could be because in general i get much better and more regular sleep than i did when i was younger. it could be because i'm better at using any otc stimulants if i need to. maybe hormonal changes play a part. i'm honestly not sure. now if i get any sudden onset of drowsiness it's due to a temporary low blood sugar condition. i'm not a diabetic but i've noticed sometimes certain foods leave me inexplicably briefly sleepy afterwards - and it's not turkey lol, it's usually some forms of carbs.   but yes for me this was quite a bothersome issue i very much dealt with in my younger adult years. i always found it extremely puzzling because it wouldn't always happen if i was feeling necessarily tired. and being temporarily bored or mentally unengaged certainly seemed to make this much more likely.   there were times when just like in this video, my lights would just seem to shut off. i would usually be able to catch myself before it became too visible but not always. occasionally i would get criticized or teased about it at work and i would do my damnedest not to have any of these moments by trying to redouble my willpower but willpower just wasn't enough.   if i had access perhaps to prescription stimulants at the time it might have helped to avoid these moments, but all i had was otc caffeine products and energy drinks, which helped somewhat but couldn't always prevent everything.

i'm a huge supporter of legalizing psilocybin mushrooms and increasing research on them but i will say that people with a history of mental illness, especially bipolar disorder and schizophrenia, should be very careful with them and may want to completely avoid them altogether. i say this because one of my college roommates ended up having a very serious case of bipolar disorder that did not become apparent until right after the first and only time he took mushrooms. that trip seemed like it helped to initiate the first major manic episode he ever experienced and after a couple nights without sleep he entered a severe psychosis that required hospitalization. he then went home to michigan for thanksgiving break where his family physician misdiagnosed his bipolar disorder as "adult adhd" and prescribed adderall, which was just like throwing fuel on a fire. i tried to get him help but wouldn't comply and his conservative christian family believed it was the devil and the evil liberal ideas he learned at our college. anyway he ended up drowning himself to death in the harbor on mackinac island like a year or two after school.   my friend killed himself in 2012 at the age of 26 but i definitely hear what you're sayin.   that's why i didn't say that "shrooms cause bipolar." i said that people with a history of mental illness should be very careful with them and may want to avoid them altogether. mental health professionals give the e act same advice and my roommate's e perience is an e ample of why they give that advice.   of course i do. psilocybin mushrooms being illegal and unregulated did not help my friend. if anything the legal prohibition on mushrooms has made them more dangerous since you never know what you're actually getting from the black market. it has also kept scientists from conducting valuable research on them. there are plenty of wonderful and even life saving medications that certain people should avoid. that doesn't mean those medications should be illegal for everyone.   you're right about this being a crazy world though, just not in the way you probably imagine. it's crazy to arrest people for taking, growing, selling, or researching psilocybin mushrooms, period.   yeah and even though that one mushroom trip preceded his first psychosis i would argue that amphetamine salts procured from other students and eventually his family physician played a much more significant role in his demise.   yeah i actually used to be prescribed 60 mg per day of adderall/amphetamine salts many years ago. people who have bipolar disorder can become manic on just normal therapeutic doses. my roommate was a 220 lb linebacker on our school's football team and he was only taking like 10 or 15 mg at a time but that was enough to get him manic.   i wouldn't let my story scare you away from psychedelics. my friend's mental illness was severe enough that i'm certain it would have come out eventually with or without that mushroom trip. if you haven't experienced any mental illness by the age of 37 then you should be in the clear when it comes to schizophrenia and bipolar disorder. just start with small doses until you know how you react to psilocybin.   my friend actually had "a good trip sitter and good preparation and dosage." his trip was fine and it was actually an overwhelmingly positive experience for him. the problem started after the shrooms wore off and he became manic, which kept him from sleeping for a couple days. sleep deprivation eventually caused him to enter a psychosis. i think it's important for me to mention this because i also used to believe that any kind of negative reaction to shrooms was avoidable with proper preparation and supervision. now i know that certain people should avoid them altogether just like with any other medication.   thanks for your input doctor!!   he didn't microdose and i've never heard of megadosing. he probably took around 1.5 to 1.75 grams if i had to guess. this was in like 2008 so it's been a while.   can't post links on youtube anymore but since you had to ask you can google "zachary warner mackinac island."

nah, just in tune with yourself. the presenter said he had an insight that his issue of guilt over taking drugs wasn't in him, but society at large. anything we experience is in us. it's only the ego that persists in its idea of separation. the world isn't changed externally, by legislation and new rules, but by the individual taking complete responsibility for his life. then he still "renders unto caesar the things that are caesar's" - that is, functions in the world - but is not of it or affected by it. surely this is the teaching of psychedelics?   does reading these words, listening to ambient sounds or feeling the clothing on your skin require thought? no - perception doesn't require thought. and yet thought is applied to everything we experience; things are good, bad or indifferent. this creates the idea of a separate world, with a past and future, full of things to attain or avoid. once our awareness is grounded in fully embodied present, impersonal experience, rather than stuck in the head and chest, we see through the separate world idea. we don't replace it with a new conceptual world, but are simply happy to be as we are. from this place - in a way which is completely mysterious to the thinking mind - action arises. this is the non-doing of the buddha. it's easy for me point to my direct experience using words, but they being concepts, can never convey the experience itself. psychedelics, like regular meditation induce direct experience. with relaxed persistence, eventually the dominance of thinking is subsumed into direct impersonal experience. that's my best go, can't add anything except please establish a regular full sensory meditation routine. this just means learning to open up awareness to your immediate experience. that means if you're sitting with eyes closed, you learn to feel the overall subtle feeling of the body while simultaneously listen to any sounds. you did this as a baby and it made you smile.

(sorry so long!) this is no longer the case in most pain management offices.  it is getting harder and harder for legit pain patients to get their medication.  they did overprescribe opiates for a long time.  here is how i explain the difference between an acute user and a chronic one.  imagine a scale 1 to 10.  one is very bad pain.  ten is a euphoric high.  let's say most human beings are at five, which is normal or baseline.  patient one is a healthy adult.  one day, p1 has an accident and suffers an injury.  she goes to the er with pain level at ten.  she is given an opiate, which brings her down to five.  in this case, the person is not "high" on the drug, she is simply experiencing pain control to bring her down to baseline.  patient 2 is the same, a healthy adult who has a minor surgery.  post-surgery his pain is at a nine.    it has been common practice to prescribe at least a month's worth of opiate pain killers for both types of patients.  so, p1 and p2 go home to recover with a month's worth of painkillers.  some people will take the meds for a few days, feel better, and either toss the rest or stash them in the cabinet.  however....many will keep taking the meds...and as the days pass, they start to heal and their pain level decreases.  now, the medication starts to bring them up to higher levels towards euphoria.  they wake up at a three, they take a pill, they go up to seven.  if they keep taking them without actual severe physical pain to treat, they will gradually creep up to level ten and experience that addicting euphoria.  my point is, opiate painkillers have a use in treating acute severe pain.  but prescribing them for a month or longer has sadly created many addicts.  now things are changing.  many doctors will not give more than three days worth after surgery or an accident.  it's for the best.  the real problem is people with chronic pain.  they are getting screwed over.  many people have issues that take them down to a one or two every day....and their opiate medication was beneficial for getting them back up to a functional five.  so many doctors are being threatened by the dea and government (who are not doctors) to withhold effective pain control from those who truly need it.  statistically, only 2% of chronic pain patients will get addicted to their meds.  most of the addictions were started by patients with acute conditions.  you cannot have an umbrella treatment plan for every person.....i agree that every kind of non-opiate med should be tried before opiates are given.  they should be a last resort.....but when you have level one or two pain, opiates are very good at what they do.  punishing those who need them to get back to a functional baseline is to going to solve the addiction issues we are facing today.  i apologize for the long comment, this is just my two cents.

it's not just the health system that's failing, although it really is: it's also the fact that our whole language of 'mental health' conceals the fact that we actually know nothing about it - we just pretend we do. we call it 'mental illness', which implies that it's something akin to a physical illness. when we say 'mental', do we mean the mind or the brain? well, most psychiatrists have the idea that it's something to do with chemical imballences, but there is absolutely no evidence to prove that it is a brain disorder. in all probability the brain is reacting in natural ways to a very unnatural set of social circumstances. the truth is we don't understand mental health or mental illness. the phenomena is a mystery. if we started by acknowledging that, as many psychologists and psychiatrists do, then this would spur research and innumerable enquiries and studies into the phenomena. not only that, but individual sufferers would not assume that they have an explanation, and would start to observe and study and try and learn themselves about it. this is what in meditation is called 'mindfullness', and is well known to be of benefit to mental wellbeing. people would explore new ways of dealing with it, and talking honestly and deeply about the experiences is known to help. therapy is an alienated, commodified form of talking about it. we should ask ourselves why our experience of mental health is so much worse then it was historically and is in other countries. we should realize that all psychiatric medication is based on the crude repression of symptoms: it is not based on an understanding of the condition, and least of all on the curing of it. it can help people survive but it will never help to overcome a mental health condition. millions of people die every year of suicide, and probably most of them would still be alive if they had someone they knew they could talk to, and who cared. in most cases people don't want to hear about it because everyone has their own struggles which are labelled 'mental illness', i.e. hopeless, and already understood. no - they are not hopeless and they are not understood, but living in a loving and supportive community, knowing unconditional love and acceptance, having true purpose, experiencing beauty and peace - these are things i think everyone knows, intuitively, would guard against the development of these forms of suffering and would heal those already sick. it is by letting go of the illusions that we understand 'mental illness' that we can hope to move forward in our understanding of it and treatment for it. i think it's clear that there are as much social and cultural and economic causes as there are biological, and there is nothing wrong with our biology: nature works perfectly. it is the unnatural, ossified, toxic, poisonous and often human made or introduced elements that destroy balance, health and wellbeing, both spiritual, mental and emotional. well, that's my two pence worth.

great discussion about this beautiful sacrament and medicine. in the beginning of the talk there was a bit of commonly cited misinformation in terms of botanical sources. yopo (anadenanthera peregrina) is overwhelmingly comprised of bufotenin, with only trace amounts of both 5-meo-dmt and n,n-dmt. one would have to ingest a massive quantity of the snuff to get a significant dose of 5-meo-dmt, and if someone did manage to get all of that powder in his or her nose the amount of bufotenin consumed would be staggering. there may be an entourage effect from the 5-meo-dmt and n,n-dmt, but yopo is primarily an experience of bufotenin. same is true for the closely related entheogenic snuff known as vilca or cebil (anadenanthera colubrina). as for chaliponga (diplopterys cabrerana), some people have long asserted that it contains 5-meo-dmt, citing several decades-old accounts that were never substantiated. recent chemical analyses have found this plant contains no 5-meo-dmt whatsoever, including samples provided by individuals who were convinced their material was full of 5-meo-dmt. instead chaliponga has been found to contain very high concentrations of n,n-dmt, much more so than chacruna (psychotria viridia) that is typically used in ayahuasca brews. that said, most people report ayahuasca made from chaliponga as having a very different quality than those made from chacruna. hopefully someone will conduct more research into this plant in the future. as for botanical sources of 5-meo-dmt, there are other traditional entheogenic snuffs from south america that are loaded with it. these are made from several virola tree species, most notably virola elongata (formerly known as virola theiodora).

alcohol is the "deadliest drug"   the british peer-reviewed journal lancet published a study titled "drug harms in the uk: a multicriteria decision analysis" on nov. 1, 2010 which ranked 20 drugs from alcohol to marijuana to tobacco based on harm factors.   individual harm (such as dependence, mortality, and impairment of mental functioning) was considered under "harm to users," while "harm to others" (such as crime, environmental damage, and international damage) took into account the number and extent of others harmed by individual drug use. the two charts below illustrate the study's conclusions using a 100 point scale where 100 is the maximum harm and zero indicates no harm. the first chart broadly illustrates all 20 drugs by "harm to users and harm to others while the second chart illustrates those drugs on 16 criteria from drug-specific mortality to dependence to family adversities.   the study concluded that alcohol was the most harmful drug overall (72 out of 100), followed by heroin (55 out of 100), and crack cocaine (54 out of 100). the most harmful drugs to users were crack cocaine, heroin, and methamphetamine (scores 37, 34, and 32, respectively), whereas alcohol, heroin, and crack cocaine were the most harmful to others (46, 21, and 17, respectively). cannabis (aka marijuana) had an overall harm score of 20, putting it in eighth place behind amphetamine (aka speed) and before ghb (aka liquid ecstasy).  you are a very perturbed person, you ever hear that?   alcohol is the deadliest drug to the body, at least in terms of weed and lsd. weed and lsd are  both impossible, or nearly impossible to od on, or hurt yourself in a significant way.   now, mentally, both weed and lsd have more "dangerous" effects, but in terms of bodily harm, lsd and weed are def safer. thanks for sharing. fascinating and interesting experience. i have only done dmt (synthetic liquid version) once last year and it was very intense. i felt a force communicating and showing my personal demons, trauma and the human story.     the issue with psychedelic enlightenment is that you might skip the grounding part. so, you go higher and higher, but your roots might not be strong enough to handle that. this can cause big fear, psychosis, more illusions or even a big setback on the path. like, going too fast. i think when doing it naturally, the trees and the roots grow accordingly. might be able to take a bit of psychedelics here and there, but it's definitely a risk regarding the balance of that.     psychedelics are just tools to reach these states. yes, it's more work doing it organically and takes more time and practice, but it's long lasting, psychedelics are like those cycle training wheels that children need for initial support, the idea is to ride the cycle without them. otherwise, people just rely on external substances to induce these states for the long term.     with that said, i'm not anti-psychedelics, i agree inner integration is vital in conjunction with them. however, from what i've come to understand in my current level of awareness is that our minds (subconscious) is very powerful on healing psychologically, emotionally and physically. at the moment, i'm focused on being more aware in my dreams to become lucid so i can use this platform for healing, exploration on the nature of consciousness and reality. i've also been practicing self hypnosis for the past 15 years and it's changed my life without any external "drugs" or "substances    lastly, i've noticed a lot of people within the new age communities and gurus spiritual bypass, by not wanting to face their inner dark shadow / traumas and taking personal responsibility in order for real healing to manifest.

  i am trying to counter this notion by a couple of people here that psych medication is some authoritarian evil perpetuated by some global cabal of an evil nefarious psychiatric profession. in truth, they are often doing the best they can with our current understanding of the brain and human behavior. there are parents feeding their kids stimulants unnecessarily and there are parents who rather see their kid fail out of school than give them stimulants. the situation is vastly more complicated than the absolutes presented here. i'm no evangelical for psychiatric medications, therapy is vastly underutilized (perhaps because so many therapists are terribly incompetent) and changes in schools and homes is seriously lacking for anyone but the wealthy. youtube comment sections are filled with people that apparently have zero grasp of the complexities of our world.. perhaps due to age or lack of education i'm not sure. anyways, i wonder what some of the people are doing on this channel about a guy's particular stance on (psychedelic) drugs with such antiquated views of drugs.. are you here as someone who partakes in self-medication with soft drugs? thanks! i'll definitely have more videos coming out with a similar subject matter. subscribe if you'd like to keep up to date! +vhormidia xmortis hey, thanks! the book is available on amazon here:  or get the kindle version free if you're a prime member: +tom buck this video is in no way meant to suggest that non-local consciousness is a rouse or that reincarnation couldn't exist or anything along those lines, but the delicate balance of our neurochemistry certainly plays a role in the way we see the world while we are living. alterations in this neurochemistry when we are near-death or immediately after death would undoubtedly change our perceptions of reality. i, too, believe that there is a lot more to be learned about what consciousness is, the difference between consciousness and sentience, how we are all universally interconnected, etc. and it is all extremely interesting, but it also doesn't discount our chemical makeup. i have looked into false moon landing theories as well as arguments against evolution and have approached them with an open mind. i personally see some of the relevant points made by the people who don't believe in the moon landing, but generally believe that we did, in fact, land on the moon. in terms of the theory of evolution, there are certainly areas in which more evidence would lend credence to the idea, however biodegradation just makes it virtually impossible for all necessary fossils to be there.  anyway, why do you ask? with all due respect, my friend, a trip is the psychiatric intervention. you are correct, though, that some people, especially those predisposed to more severe mental illnesses like schizophrenia may not want to participate, but even then plant spirit shamanism can be of service, with schizophrenia often being compared to the shamanic state itself, a vestige of our hunter gatherer origins, it's been posited that the place of the schizophrenic was the shaman in our prehistory. further, anthropologists have found virtually no instance of mental illness in the ayahuasca culture of the quechua. i believe it is a fear of the unknown associated with ego death and exploration of new realms, real or imagined i have wrestled with this question, and honestly still do not know. whether it is real or just a product of the mind, though, the experience is still the same. in fact, everything you perceive in ordinary life could be construed as a product of the mind i believe that for the most part these substances simply allow your brain to perceive things in a way that is different from our ordinary means of perception. that is to say that, while those spirals are always there, our brains are not attuned to them usually, because they are not of use for navigating our reality in a way that allows for collection of food/goods, which is vital to the survival of the organism. your 'default neural mode' as it is sometimes referred to allows for a narrow purview to perform required tasks, with very defined, clear cut differences between visual and audio cortex, etc. these distinctions are not so hard and fast in altered states. niklas, i do not know you, and i mean no judgement by this, but it sounds like you may be in crisis. i recommend speaking to a trusted clergy member, counselor, or psychiatric/psychological professional if you need help. best of luck!

for the rest of your life is incorrect. your brain chemistry can repair itself after some time, it just takes longer to get back to normal. and there are great supplements that can help get you sharp again. you fuck yourself up if you are abusing. people who have adhd that take the medication responsibly often don't see much issues. i've seen many people who will take breaks when they aren't in school, etc. and some people just don't react well to stimulant medication anyway or have addictive tendencies. everyone is different, the same standard can't be applied to everyone. yes, your brain will get used to the dopamine release from adderall if you are taking it regularly so when you stop taking it, it will be lower than before. but it won't fuck you up for the rest of your life unless you are a long term user and/or abused the medication. you may not feel great, but same often goes for the process of getting off of antidepressants. that's what i hate about these arguments. a lot of people want to throw around advice about how adderall and other stimulant adhd meds will ruin your life and your brain, but coming from someone who doesn't have adhd that doesn't mean much to me. it will have a different affect on those that do not have adhd and are therefore not taking the meds as prescribed and are abusing. i haven't had any issues with adderall comedown either and feel fine on days i don't take it. how am i different? i was diagnosed with adhd and take it as prescribed (i actually don't even take it every day). plus i feel like people with adhd are more familiar with the ups and downs that come naturally with lower dopamine production, that it doesn't feel like their whole world has shifted when the adderall wears off. if anything i just notice i have less ups and downs on days i take meds. and that counts way before i ever started taking them.

back when i was in university i came close to taking my own life. i wasn't able to drink because my emotions were too uncontrollable  , and i stopped going out with my friends to parties etc. i was diagnosed with bpd & cptsd a few years later.  one day about 20 of us went to a rave, and i was going completely sober. one of them suggested i take mdma instead of alcohol, and i took some that night because i thought i had nothing to lose.   now i'm older, i understand the dangers of street drugs, but that night saved my life. the mdma completely silenced my depression, my critical voice, my ptsd flashbacks. i was never the same after that night, and i even tell my therapist now, that it completely changed my perspective on life. i was able to process my difficult emotions without feeling them so heavily, and i was able to think differently about a lot of things.   i know that was the least scientific experiment possible, but i knew that night that mdma was something else entirely compared to what the mainstream idea of it was.   i'm so greatful that the field of psychology / psychiatry is now taking psychedelics seriously.

my mother was a psychology major in college and knew i had adhd (add was the term back then) since i was about 5 years old. i did poorly in school, lost a lot of things, talked too much in class, and was ostracized by classmates and teachers alike for being annoying or strange. depending on my mother's mood, she would tell me my add is "not my fault" or yell at me for being "too add," all the while hiding my symptoms from my pediatric doctor's because she didn't want me to get on stimulant medication. this had devastating consequences for my self-worth and mental health which i'm still dealing with to this day.   over the years though, i learned to manage a few of my symptoms via planners, google calendars, and phone reminders. i ended up doing pretty good in school becuase of my work ethic but high school and college were still hard on my mental health because of my executive dysfunction. i am now 22 years old and finally secured a diagnosis only last week (hence why i'm here, watching this video at 1.25 speed) but my diagnosis ended up being the unspecified type instead of the inattentive type as it should have been only because my mother, for whatever reason, is still against me getting on medication so she lied about my childhood symptoms on the survey/form (i.e. pretended i was a neurotypical kid and had no issues in school or relationships).   anyways. for anyone who is reading this, there is nothing wrong with you, even if your parents say so. and i hope you'll be able to get a diagnosis and get on medication even with the world against you. you got this!

magic mushrooms are very, very bad as they can cause hallucinogen persisting perception disorder (hppd). nobody warned me magic mushrooms can cause hppd before i tried them. now i am suffering. my eyes are super light-sensitive. i can no longer look at computer screens without dimming them and wearing sun-glasses. i was still hallucinating days after my last intake of magic mushrooms (seeing triangles and other geometric shapes and colourful galaxies on the backs of my eyelids when i'd close my eyes, seeing halos around letters which makes reading uncomfortable, and seeing halos around people, objects, and trails behind cars or people as they move). i also now have flashes of light in my visual field which makes my vision less sharp than before. not knowing they are an illegal substance in canada, i purchased them from an online store from british columbia. they arrived in a factory-type bag that looked legit. there was absolutely no warning on the bag that magic mushrooms can cause hppd in some people after only one use. had i known about this potential side-effect, i never would have tried them. they did give me a pleasant euphoria and they did lift my depression, but very temporarily. still, that good feeling, for me, was not worth, the hppd i got. i tried them only 3 times. the first time about 2 weeks ago, about 3 grams. i had unpleasant hallucinations (the bathroom tile patterns seemed to pop out of the tiles and float around, the grout between the tiles seemed to flow like rivers, the walls and ceilings seemed to be quivering). along with those scary hallucinations came the temporary pleasant feeling of euphoria or being "high" which temporarily masked my feelings of depression and sadness. my depression seemed to be alleviated for the next 3 days, after that first dose, then it came back. a week later, i tried micro-dosing to avoid hallucinations, but in hopes of still receiving some of the "benefit" of depression relief. i took 0.5 grams on a friday, and then another 0.5 grams on a saturday. this time, i measured them out with a precision scale i obtained in the meantime, so i know that i did not consume more than 0.5 grams each of these last 2 times i tried magic mushrooms. however, on the sunday after my last (saturday) use, while looking at a computer screen at work, my vision began to completely fade. at first, everything appeared to be in a thick mist or fog. then the visual fields of both of my eyes turned white completely. for a temporary time, i was unable to see anything. this frightened me so that i went in a darkened room to rest my eyes, and i called an ambulance. ever since, i have had vision problems i never used to have. i did research and found out that many people who tried magic mushrooms do develop hppd. by some estimates, 60% of hallucinogen users (whether of magic mushrooms, lsd, ecstasy, dmt, ayahuasca, peyote, mescaline, psilocybin, etc.) develop hppd. some develop it in a mild form so that they hardly notice it. some are not even aware they have it. up to 5% of hallucinogen users develop it  in such a severe form that it disables them: they often cannot read, cannot safely walk outside without assistance as they cannot properly see where they are going, cannot work, cannot study in school... in those 4 to 5% of cases, hppd is so severe it is life-crippling. as there is no cure for it, some people have it for months, years, or in some cases for the rest of their lives. although i agree that magic-mushroom euphoria feels great and is highly effective for temporary depression relief (at least it was in my case), in my experience and opinion, it is not worth the risk of getting hppd (which is something i believe i got in a thankfully more mild form). some of my symptoms (such as hallucinations when i close my eyes days after the last use of the mushrooms have thankfully now gone away. but some stil persist: the halos around letters, causing eye strain when i read. the photo-sensitivity and inability to look at bright computer screens for long without sun-glasses. ever since my last use of the mushrooms, my eyes have also been much drier than normal. i wonder if the neurotoxin in them affected the nerves that control my lacrimal (tear) glands, reducing the natural flow of tears as eye lubrication. i am now using artificial tears every day. slowly the strange eye dryness is getting better. the halos and flashes of light in my field of vision still make my experience of seeing this world less beautiful and less sharp then before. in spite of the nice euphoria, i do not recommend the use of magic mushrooms. i don't think the risk of developing hppd potentially for life is worth the temporary good feeling. anyone serious about protecting people's health when speaking of magic mushrooms should warn would-be users about hppd as a potential side-effect. it does not occur in all people. i know some men who used magic mushrooms who did not experience this effect after several uses. i am a woman, and smaller in body size than they. maybe this is why the compounds in mushrooms affected me faster and more severely than they did these several men. however, even men can get hppd. many you tubers both male and female complain they got it after the use of magic mushrooms, ecstasy, or lsd. another harmful effects of such hallucinogens can be de-personalization and de-realization disorders (dp / dr), where nothing seems real, where one has the sense that one is living in a dream, where one feels disconnected from one's body and the world, and where one does not even recognize one's face in the mirror. another effect i personally experienced is a change in colour perception. colours look a bit different than before. here is a video titled "hppd reality: an unrecognized occurrence" by a you tuber who got hppd who shows others how it looks like in his more severe case: https://www.youtube.com just because some of the magic-mushroom enthusiasts have not gotten hppd yet, it does not mean that they won't in the future or that others can't. i certainly did in a milder form, and the above you tuber, with channel name "hppd reality", did in a more severe form. if mushroom enthusiasts care about their viewers, they should warn them about the possibility of hppd. even though it does not happen in all cases, it is certainly a real risk of using magic mushrooms. if there was a warning label on the bag of dried mushrooms that came in the mail, i never would have used them and partially ruined my previously good vision. there were no warnings whatsoever, even though magic mushrooms contain drug substances and should come with warnings, just like pharmaceuticals do. i now realize that there is a good reason they were classed as prohibited "schedule i" drugs in many places in the world, and i have a greater appreciation for us president's nixon's "war on drugs" than i did before. if only somebody could design a drug that has the beneficial depression-lifting effect of psilicybin and psilocin, but without the harmful potential effects of magic mushrooms, such as hppd and dp/dr, then it would be the perfect anti-depression drug. unfortunately, the world does not have that yet.

nice theory! theory 1: lsd removes the perception filters we have developed ever since we were tiny children.  newborns and babies don't have these filters developed yet, everything is so unbelievably fascinating to them: shapes, colours, noises etc.  reality is buzzing with magical activity.  once these perception filters are fully-developed (say by the age of 3 or 4) then reality has settled into the steady static solid realm we all know.    an adult on lsd has the advantage over the baby in that he or she has lived a life: has developed eyesight, hearing and appreciation.  to have a chance of having these filters temporarily removed creates in the adult that same sense of magical wonder, which we can barely describe but at least we remember it, cherish it and attempt to reconcile it with our steady world.

psilocybin should be enough man and as you suggested more accessible. give it enough time and it can do amazing things. i've been using it on and off, solo, for 15 years. i managed to get clear of 8 years of alcohol addiction, 12 years smoking cigarettes and sporadic abuse of opiates. it's bloody challenging work and i had many brutal trips, unfortunately *it's more risky doing it alone so extra attention needs to be paid to set/setting, dose* etc. i got cocky a few times and got too ambitious with the dose and got my fucking ass kicked, the type of experience that rocks you to the core of who you think you are. i'm open to chat about it further if need be. i've been using psilocybin, solo, for many years now and although i am intrigued by using psychedelics in the ceremonial group setting, i find the social aspect of things very challenging. i attended a holotropic breathwork workshop a little while back and found speaking to the group, before and after the breathwork, was utterly terrifying- more so than writhing on the floor submerged in my unconscious.    yeah for sure it will be rough mate. i had post addiction withdrawal symptoms (paws) for about 4 months after i stopped binge drinking. probably not as savage as the opiate withdrawal, but it takes a lot of perseverance to get through that phase. all the best.    yeah, if you can find the right group. i have a friend who ran some plant medicine ceremonies out of her clinic but the price was very restrictive. there's actually a lot you can resolve in a comfortable room by yourself.    sure, if you find legit facilitators i believe it can be really helpful, i agree. i worked with some good, honest facilitators at the breathwork workshop i attended but i didn't get much out of it at all compared to some of my solo mushroom trips. i certainly don't have regrets about it, i'm just sharing my personal experience.

friend's son tripped on dramamine...then took off with one of his friends in his car, leaving one behind.  the one left behind would stare and mumble.  he'd stand in the pantry and mumble, friend would say, "are you hungry?  you want something to eat?"  (mumble and nod.)  she made him soup.  he'd mumble something then laugh.  soon, the friend that went with came walking back.  this is when we found out what they were on---he'd been kicked out of the car because there was a blue horse on the side of the road that needed a ride, and there wasn't room, so, he chose the horse over his friend.  i told my friend to call state patrol and the poison center, and, "don't let him fall asleep!"  icy roads, paranoid of what i'd find...come to ambulances and staters, flashing lights, see his car...oh shit!  i see him standing there with a trooper, i jump out yelling, "bobby!  bobby!  are you okay???"  the trooper asks, "do you know this young man?"  no, i always jump out at accident scenes and yell, 'bobby! bobby!  are you alright?'  he was fine, the accident was another car, but he'd seen the lights, pulled over, and was found trying to catch invisible butterflies in the middle of the highway.  trooper took him home, but *i* ended up in the ambulance, as the stress caused my blood sugar to bottom out.  26.  i had to sit there while they fed me candy until it was close to normal (about 90).  they took him to the hospital to hydrate him and flush the drugs out.  he was talking to people who weren't there, smoking an imaginary joint, and cussing out his mother, calling her a "fucking cunt".  the mumbling friend?  he thought he had been speaking normally, and couldn't understand why we were acting so weird and couldn't understand him.

the secretion of the sonoran desert toadtechnically it is a poison not a venomfunctions as a defense mechanism against predation, not as a tool to subdue prey. as for 5-meo-dmt, it is possibly the most powerful and profound experience a human being could have short of actual death. it is definitely not for everybody. for those who can fully surrender, 5meo can be a life-changing, paradigm-shattering union with god, divine consciousness, source energy, creation, or whatever language you prefer. an experience of infinite divine love, transcendent peace, and ultimate truth. liberation from suffering and from the self and the egoic mind. for those who fight dissolution of the ego, 5meo can be utterly terrifying and traumatic. once again this is not for everybody, as it can destabilize a person who is not able to surrender and who is unable to integrate such a profound and powerful experience. by the way, there is a far better documentary about 5meo than the film referenced in this video. it is called bufo alvarius: the underground secret. also worth mentioning that humans produce 5meo endogenouslyalbeit in small quantitiesjust as we do n,n-dmt (aka dmt), which is the visionary component of the ayahuasca brew that has been used by indigenous peoples of the amazon rainforest for millennia. in fact dmt has recently been observed in human cerebrospinal fluid at concentrations nearing those of serotonin. all of which begs the question: why do these substances exist and why are humans wired to receive them in this way?

 it's overly simplistic to imagine dopamine can be easily raised or lowered without serious side effects in the body. the entire muscle system uses dopamine in quite a different way than the brain, but it's still dopamine! i'd be very careful with "i cannot get addicted".  this was how the opioid epidemic started, because oxycontin makers assured doctors of how many people take opioids for medical reasons without getting addicted. it turns out just a little extra stress, or even just the desire to work more, leads to addiction. i too, could pick up or drop smoking in my teens and early 20s. then it became routine. in my late 20s, it took exactly 20 cigarettes to get me addicted again, and i'd buy another pack after the first. it's been a struggle through my 40s.   it's really dangerous to think you a a special exception.  and the science isn't there to explain how dopamine is actually involved. there are at least five different dopamine receptors. a serious dopamine deficiency looks like parkinson's disease, not just a bored, unmotivated person. in that disease, medicines to raise some dopamine needs to be taken with others that will lower it outside the brain. blithely associating behaviors with dopamine levels is a fool's game. and making that comment just raised engagement levels on youtube's algorithms, effectively discounting your actual advice. so, good luck on your physics studies!
